{"title_page": "Broken Age", "text_new": "{{Infobox video game\n| title = Broken Age\n| image = File:Broken Age cover art.jpg\n| developer = [[Double Fine Productions]]\n| publisher = Double Fine Productions\n| caption = Cover art featuring Vella (left) and Shay (right) in their respective homes\n| director = [[Tim Schafer]]\n| producer = Greg Rice\n| designer = \n| programmer = Oliver Franzke<br />Anna Kipnis\n| artist = Lee Petty<br />[[Nathan Stapley]]\n| writer = Tim Schafer\n| composer = [[Peter McConnell]]\n| engine = [[Moai (software)|Moai]]\n| platforms = [[Microsoft Windows]], [[OS X]], [[Linux]], [[Ouya]], [[iOS]], [[Android (operating system)|Android]], [[PlayStation 4]], [[PlayStation Vita]], [[Xbox One]], [[Nintendo Switch]]\n| released = {{Collapsible list\n  |title = April 28, 2015\n  |titlestyle = font-weight:normal;background:transparent;text-align:left\n  |'''''Act 1'''''<br />'''Windows''', '''OS X''', '''Linux'''<br />January 14, 2014 <small>(Backer Beta)</small><ref name=\"polygonouya\">{{cite web |url=http://www.polygon.com/2013/2/6/3961578/double-fine-adventure-the-cave-ouya-dice-2013 |publisher=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] |title=Double Fine Adventure and The Cave coming to Ouya |date=2013-02-06 |accessdate=2013-07-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=First act of Broken Age coming to Steam in January|url=http://www.gamesradar.com/first-act-broken-age-coming-steam-january/|work=GamesRadar|accessdate=11 December 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2014-01-10-broken-age-episode-one-comes-to-early-access-on-tuesday | title = Broken Age Episode One comes to Early Access on Tuesday | publisher = [[Eurogamer]] | first = Jeffrey | last = Mutelef | date = 2014-01-10 | accessdate = 2014-01-10 }}</ref><br />January 28, 2014 <small>(Public)</small><ref>http://store.steampowered.com/app/232790/</ref><br />'''Ouya'''<br />May 30, 2014<br />'''iOS'''<br />June 12, 2014<br />'''Android'''<br />April 28, 2015<br />'''PS4''', '''PS Vita'''<br />{{vgrelease|NA|April 28, 2015<ref name=\"Act2\"/>|EU|April 29, 2015<ref name=\"Act2\"/>}}\n  |'''''Act 2'''''<br />{{vgrelease|NA|April 28, 2015<ref name=\"Act2\"/>|EU|April 29, 2015<ref name=\"Act2\">{{cite web|last1=Silva|first1=Marty|title=Broken Age Act 2 release date announced|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2015/03/25/broken-age-act-2-release-date-announced|website=IGN|accessdate=March 25, 2015|date=March 25, 2015}}</ref>}}\n  }}\n| genre = [[Point-and-click adventure]] \n| modes = [[Single-player video game|Single-player]]\n}}\n\n'''''Broken Age''''' is a [[point-and-click adventure]] [[video game]] developed and published by [[Double Fine]].<ref name=\"polygon name\">{{cite web | url = http://www.polygon.com/2013/3/24/4141386/double-fine-adventure- | title = Broken Age is the official title of Double Fine Adventure | first = Alexa Ray | last = Corriea | publisher = [[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] | date = 2013-03-24 | accessdate = 2013-03-24 }}</ref> ''Broken Age'' was game director [[Tim Schafer]]'s first return to the genre since 1998's ''[[Grim Fandango]]'', and was released for [[Microsoft Windows]], [[Mac OS X]], [[Linux]], [[iOS]], [[Android (operating system)|Android]], [[PlayStation 4]], [[PlayStation Vita]], and [[Xbox One]] platforms. The game was developed in two acts; the first was released on January 28, 2014 (two weeks earlier for Kickstarter backers), and the second was released on April 28, 2015. A retail version of the complete game for Windows, OS X, and Linux, published by [[Nordic Games GmbH|Nordic Games]], was released on April 28, 2015.<ref name=\"retail\">{{cite web | title = Broken Age is out now | url = http://www.nordicgames.at/index.php/article/broken_age_is_out_now | publisher = [[Nordic Games GmbH|Nordic Games]] | date = 2015-04-28 | accessdate = 2015-04-29 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150502074846/http://www.nordicgames.at/index.php/article/broken_age_is_out_now | archive-date = 2015-05-02 | url-status = dead }}</ref> A [[Nintendo Switch]] version was released on September 13, 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nintendoeverything.com/broken-age-sees-surprise-release-on-switch/|title=Broken Age sees surprise release on Switch|last=Richards|first=Brian|date=2018-09-13|work=Nintendo Life|accessdate=2019-03-23}}</ref>\n\n''Broken Age'' began under the working title ''Double Fine Adventure'' as a [[Kickstarter]] [[crowdfunding|crowd-funded]] project promoted by Double Fine and [[2 Player Productions]] in February 2012. Though originally a goal of only $400,000 was set to cover the costs of development and documentary filming, ''Broken Age'' became the largest crowd-funded video game project at the time, raising over 3.45 million dollars from more than 87,000 backers within the month. It remains one of [[List of highest funded crowdfunding projects|the highest-backed crowd-funded projects]] of any type, and its success helped to establish [[crowdfunding in video games|Kickstarter and other crowd-funding mechanisms]] as a viable alternative to traditional [[venture capital]] and [[video game publisher|publisher]] funding for niche video game titles. The game's development was chronicled by an episodic series of documentaries produced by 2 Player Productions.\n\n==Gameplay==\n''Broken Age'' is a [[point-and-click adventure game]], where the player-controlled character can be directed to move about the screen, examine objects, and talk to non-player characters to learn more about the game world. The game features two playable characters, each located in seemingly separate worlds; the player can switch from one character to the other via the game's interface at any time, but otherwise these characters do not interact in any direct way. The game employs context-sensitive actions instead of using verb lists as early adventure games would use, as Schafer stated that in essence, \"there really was always one verb, which was 'interact with'\" and opted for the more modern approach.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.polygon.com/2013/11/3/5059690/broken-age-preview | title = Broken Age built around context-based interactions, not a list of verbs | publisher = [[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] | date =2013-11-03 | accessdate = 2013-11-03 | first  = Megan | last =  Farokhmanesh  }}</ref> Each character has separate item inventories as they collect objects; items can then be used by dragging them onto context-sensitive areas on the screen or combined with other inventory items.\n\n==Plot==\n===Act 1===\n''Broken Age'' tells the story of two teenagers with no immediately apparent connection, each \"seeking to break the tradition in their lives\".<ref name=\"polygon name\"/>\n\nVella Tartine (voiced by [[Masasa Moyo]]) is a young woman living in the Badlands, a land ravaged by the Mogs, giant creatures that come from beyond a wall called the Plague Dam. They are appeased by the sacrifice of young girls at a number of Maiden's Feasts held at various villages. They appear every fourteen years for those maidens. Vella is chosen to be sacrificed to Mog Chothra at the feast in her hometown of Sugar Bunting (formerly a town made up of warriors named Steel Bunting) but concludes that if the monster could be killed, the rituals could be ended. She finds a way to escape the beast's attack and ends up in Meriloft, a small colony which rests on a cluster of semisolid clouds. They are dealing with the aftermath of their own Feast, affirming her belief that the rites are disastrous to their people and should be ended. She then finds her way to a nearby port town, Shellmound, where they are preparing for their own Feast. There she discovers the Dead Eye God's temple, which turns out to be an ancient spaceship, the Maloruna, half-buried by the sand. She is able to wake its pilot, Alex, from his three hundred year stasis, and he helps her to rig the ship's scanning system to fire a laser at Mog Chothra when he shows up for the Feast. Vella's plan works, and she is able to bring down the creature.\n\nShay Volta (voiced by [[Elijah Wood]]) is a young man and seemingly the only passenger on the spaceship Bossa Nostra (Bassinostra), an \"incubator vessel\". The ship's computer has two [[artificial intelligence]]s (A.I.s). The computer's diurnal A.I., named \"MOM\", acts as a mother figure to Shay, occupying him with infantile \"missions\" and boring routines, while preventing him from learning about or exploring anything farther than the outside of the ship. The computer's nocturnal A.I. acts as a father figure to Shay and is more understanding of Shay's desire for independence, but appears to be too busy to spend time with Shay. The computer asserts that he is part of ''Project Dandelion'', a last-ditch effort by his home planet, Loruna, to protect Shay (the only survivor of his race following the planet's destruction) and try to find a home for him. When Shay sneaks into the bowels of the ship, he finds a stowaway named Marek wearing a wolf costume. Marek claims that, unbeknownst to him, a war rages in the galaxy, and tells Shay that he needs his help to save some innocent creatures who have been imprisoned in different areas of the galaxy as a result. Marek guides Shay through various missions against the computer's knowledge and control, trying to rescue a number of the creatures at each location before their position is discovered by an enemy force. During one of these rescues, Shay refuses to leave the last creature behind, causing the ship to be attacked, and trapping Marek under a pile of debris. In the ensuing chaos, Shay is knocked unconscious.\n\nAct 1 ends when Vella, going up to the downed Mog Chothra, discovers the monster is mechanical. Shay emerges confused from inside, revealing his belief of being in space was merely part of an illusion and he was unwittingly controlling Mog Chothra. Vella attempts to punch Shay but misses and falls into Mog Chothra's mouth. The mouth closes behind her, leaving them both trapped in each other's worlds, uncertain of what to do in their new surroundings.\n\n=== Act 2 ===\nShay, trapped outside Mog Chothra, is reminded that the ship's AIs are actually his real parents; his father, Ray Volta, stuck outside with Shay, warns that his mother is still trapped within. As Ray tries to find a way back inside, Shay, recovered from his shock of the outside world, takes a look around when the ship takes off, stranding them there. Shay meets Alex, learning that he was a previous subject of ''Project Dandelion''. Alex was born on his ship, the Maloruna, a Diamond Age Dandelion Cruiser. His parents never showed him any pictures of Loruna. They lived for about 20 years after the crash (280 years ago), and then died three months apart from each other; their passing was one of the reasons why he went into ''crysolation''. Before his ship's crash, Alex had a talking cello named Marek who told him to hack the controls and rescue innocent creatures, just like Shay, who realizes that they were really capturing girls.\n\nShay offers to help repair Alex's ship to return to Loruna, where Alex believes Shay's ship is heading. Meanwhile, Vella (having accidentally reactivated the computer's autopilot) works her way into the ship and encounters Marek, who is still pinned under debris. Marek directs Vella to get into the control room as to stop Shay's mother, Hope Volta. Vella pretends that she is Shay to trick his mother into opening the door, but they are both quickly locked inside by Marek, who reveals himself to be Marekai, a member of a race called the Thrush. Marekai told Hope their world was dying so she went forth and found salvation, as many have before her: their ships were the Mogs. It turns out that Loruna is not a planet but an empire beyond the Plague Dam. He then directs the ship to deliver Vella there. Meanwhile, Shay makes his way through Shellmound and Meriloft to find parts to repair Alex's ship and go back to Loruna. He retraces Vella's journey and talks to the people with whom she interacted in Act 1 and her family, as they search for her.\n\nBack on Vella's side: Vella frees herself and Hope, and the true nature of ''Project Dandelion'' is revealed: the Thrush, believing the rest of the beings on the planet to be filled with disease, barricaded themselves with the humans whom they govern beyond the Plague Dam, and over the generations, modified their normal human DNA to become \"superior\"; but also lost certain traits necessary for survival. Project Dandelion has been used to send out uniquely attuned human children from their normal human population who could locate a special maiden via the Maiden's Feasts to \"true\" their bloodline. Vella was the one Shay selected amongst the other Maidens (who are alive but held captive), and the Thrush is planning on killing her to incorporate her genetics into theirs.\n\nKnowing her potential fate, Vella creates a bomb from the ship's power core to destroy the hangar where all of the Mog ships are kept. After planting the bomb, Hope and Vella set their ship to escape. Meanwhile, Shay helps Alex reactivate his ship and they set a course directly for the Plague Dam, accompanied by Shay's father and Vella's family. Right outside the gate, the two ships collide and the Thrush starts attacking the ships, which are both stuck on autopilot. Shay and Vella work together to cause Alex's ship reactor to overheat, melting both ships together. Everyone but Shay escapes, and Vella and Hope encourage him to jump to safety; Shay jumps, just missing a ledge, but is saved by the noble sacrifice of one of his robots, Grabbin' Gary. The fused ships soon solidify, forming a bridge between the mainland and the Plague Dam. Shay and Vella finally meet. After a moment's hesitation, they smile at one another.\n\nWithin the credit sequence, it is shown that the Thrush is deposed from power, the Plague Dam is demolished, and the humans of Loruna and the Badlands form a peaceful alliance. Many images in the credits include the notable people, animals, and machines shown throughout the game living much better lives.\n\n==Development==\n\n===Announcement and fund-raising===\n[[File:Double Fine Adventure logo.jpg|thumb|right|Promotional art used to promote the project on Kickstarter, with the Double Fine two-headed baby logo, used as part of the rewards for Kickstarter backers]]\n\n''Double Fine Adventure'' was announced by way of a [[Kickstarter]] project initiated on February 8, 2012. The idea came after Double Fine's [[Tim Schafer]] was interviewed for 2 Player Productions' upcoming Kickstarter-funded documentary on the game ''[[Minecraft]]''.<ref name=\"pcworld 2player\">{{cite web | url = http://www.pcworld.com/article/250101/2_player_productions_interview.html#tk.rss_main | title = 2 Player Productions Interview | first = Dave | last= Daw | date = 2012-02-17 | accessdate= 2012-02-17 | work = [[PC World (magazine)|PC World]] }}</ref> After the interview, Schafer and 2 Player discussed the idea of the production company filming a documentary about Double Fine as a future project.<ref name=\"pcworld 2player\"/> Double Fine had already had experience as a studio being filmed during development of ''[[Psychonauts]]'' for an episode of [[G4 (U.S. TV channel)|G4 TV]]'s ''[[Icons (TV series)|Icons]]'' series.<ref name=\"vb interview\">{{cite web | url = https://venturebeat.com/2012/02/21/double-fines-tim-schafer-on-kickstarter-success-i-did-not-expect-this-interview/ | title = Double Fine's Tim Schafer on Kickstarter success: It can happen again (interview) | publisher = [[Venture Beat]] | date = 2012-02-21 | accessdate = 2012-02-21 | first = Stefanie | last = Fogel }}</ref> When 2 Player completed the ''Minecraft'' project, around November 2011, they wanted to create a more in-depth documentary, recognizing that Double Fine had the right type of environment where such a documentary would be possible.<ref name=\"pcworld 2player\"/> The two studios began to work out the specifics of the project, but Schafer realized that publisher interference would make an honest portrayal of game development impossible. Double Fine lacked the resources to self-fund a game, and 2 Player lacked the ability to fund the film, so the two companies elected to crowd-fund the project on Kickstarter, a method Schafer had seen successfully used to raise much smaller amounts for independent game developers. The creation of a new game was initially considered \"kind of as a sidenote\" by Schafer to accommodate the documentary filming.<ref name=\"kickstarter\"/><ref name=\"gb interview\"/>\n\nThe [[adventure game]] genre was selected to offer the public a product that would not have existed without their support, and help to distinguish the project from the developer's publisher-financed work.<ref name=\"gb interview\">{{cite web | url = http://www.giantbomb.com/news/16-million-and-counting/3981/ |title = $1.6 Million and Counting | first = Patrick | last = Klepek | date = 2012-02-13 | accessdate = 2012-02-13 | publisher = [[Giant Bomb]] }}</ref> Schafer, a veteran of [[LucasArts adventure games|LucasArts]], has long been associated with adventure games, a genre that has long been stigmatized as commercially niche, particularly since the release of Schafer's own ''[[Grim Fandango]]''.<ref name=\"kickstarter\">{{cite web | url = http://www.kickstarter.com/projects/66710809/double-fine-adventure | title = Double Fine Adventure | publisher = [[Double Fine Productions]] | date = 2012-02-08 | accessdate = 2012-02-09 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gilbert|first=Andrew Simon|date=2017|title=Crowdfunding Nostalgia: Kickstarter and the Revival of Classic PC Game Genres|journal=The Computer Games Journal|language=en|volume=6|issue=1\u20132|pages=17\u201332|doi=10.1007/s40869-017-0031-x|issn=2052-773X}}</ref> In his pitch to the public, Schafer argued that funding for such a project would be very difficult to come by, stating \"If I were to go to a publisher right now and pitch an adventure game, they'd laugh in my face.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wired.co.uk/news/archive/2012-02/09/double-fine-kickstarter |title=Tim Schafer persuades fans to finance next adventure game |work=[[Wired UK]] |date=2012-02-09 |accessdate=2012-02-10 |first=Mark |last=Brown |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120212003117/http://www.wired.co.uk/news/archive/2012-02/09/double-fine-kickstarter |archivedate=2012-02-12 }}</ref> Ron Gilbert, another ex-LucasArts adventure game designer at Double Fine, has long expressed this sentiment, writing in his personal blog, \"From first-hand experience, I can tell you that if you even utter the words \"adventure game\" in a meeting with a publisher you can just pack up your spiffy concept art and leave.  You'd get a better reaction by announcing that you have the plague.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://grumpygamer.com/3258434 |title=Adventure Games (via) |date=2005-07-23 |accessdate=2012-02-17 |publisher=[[Ron Gilbert]] |first=Ron |last=Gilbert |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070612160141/http://grumpygamer.com/3258434 |archivedate=2007-06-12 }}</ref>  Schafer explained that the game will not be \"museum\" or \"nostalgia\" work, but instead \"It's going to be fresh and feel modern and feel like what the next game would have been if I'd made one straight after ''Grim Fandango''\".<ref name=\"eurogamer gdc\"/>\n\nThe Kickstarter drive was launched in early February 2012 so that, regardless of its success, Schafer would be able to talk about it during the 2012 [[Game Developers' Conference]] in early March.<ref name=\"gb interview\"/> Double Fine set the goal for the project at $400,000, with $100,000 allocated to the film production and $300,000 for the game. Although this was the largest goal of any gaming project yet on Kickstarter, it was the lowest budget the company had worked with, and a small fraction of the budget of the company's previous downloadable games, which cost around $2 million.<ref name=\"kickstarter\"/><ref name=\"gb interview\"/> Schafer admitted that a game made for this budget would be \"hobbled,\" and that the budget was chosen because it was the absolute minimum he thought he could make an adventure game for.<ref name=\"gb interview\"/> The two had originally envisioned a total $200,000 budget, a typical cost for an [[iOS]] game, but Schafer had doubts about whether Double Fine could deliver a game for such a low cost.<ref name=\"gb interview\"/>\n\nVarious incentives were given to those that pledged $15 or more, including the game itself, early [[beta (software)|beta]] access to the game, access to private community areas to discuss the game, prints, and invitations to meet with the Double Fine staff.<ref name=\"kickstarter\"/> Further rewards were added through a second update two weeks into the effort, including digital soundtracks, physical copies of the game and documentary, and an art book.<ref name=\"eurogamer update2\">{{cite web | url = http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2012-02-24-double-fine-adventure-will-likely-be-old-school-2d | title = Double Fine Adventure will likely be \"old school\" 2D | first = Fred | last = Dutton | date = 2012-02-24 | accessdate= 2012-02-24 | publisher = [[Eurogamer]] }}</ref> In launching the Kickstarter project, Double Fine claimed it was the first major studio to use the model for the funding of a game.<ref name=\"cnn\">{{cite web | url = http://whatsnext.blogs.cnn.com/2012/02/10/when-making-a-game-is-a-game-in-itself/ | title = When making a game is a game in itself | first = John | last = Sutter | date = 2012-02-10 | accessdate = 2012-02-10 | publisher = CNN | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120211221839/http://whatsnext.blogs.cnn.com/2012/02/10/when-making-a-game-is-a-game-in-itself/ | archive-date = 2012-02-11 | url-status = dead }}</ref>\n\nWithin nine hours, the Kickstarter project had exceeded the $400,000 goal.<ref>{{cite web|last=Yin-Poole |first=Wesley |url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2012-02-09-psychonauts-developer-double-fine-making-fan-funded-adventure-game |title=Psychonauts developer Double Fine making fan-funded adventure game |publisher = [[Eurogamer]] |date=2012-02-09 |accessdate=2012-02-09}}</ref> Within 24 hours, it had surpassed $1 million.<ref name=\"usatoday 1m\">{{cite web | url = https://www.usatoday.com/tech/gaming/story/2012-02-09/game-funding-crowdsourced/53031998/1 | title = Video game makers use crowd-sourced funding for new project | first = Mike | last = Snider | date = 2012-02-09 | accessdate = 2012-02-09 | work = [[USA Today]] }}</ref> As the funds raised approached $1.35 million, Schafer noted that the total had already exceeded the budget for ''[[Day of the Tentacle]]'' ($600,000) and was nearing the budget for ''[[Full Throttle (1995 video game)|Full Throttle]]'' ($1.5 million).<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2012-02-10-double-fine-adventure-passes-day-of-the-tentacle-budget | title = Double Fine Adventure passes Day of the Tentacle budget | first = Fred | last = Dutton | date = 2012-02-10 | accessdate = 2012-02-10 | publisher = [[Eurogamer]] }}</ref>  Kickstarter stated on the day after its start that the Double Fine effort is the most successful to date, having attracted more backers than any prior effort in the site's history<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.thestar.com/article/1128741--game-developer-raises-700-000-in-less-than-a-day-using-crowd-funding-site-kickstarter | title = Game developer raises $700,000 in less than a day using crowd-funding site Kickstarter | work = [[Toronto Star]] | date = 2012-02-09 | accessdate = 2012-02-09 | first = Raju | last = Mudhar }}</ref> while others have noted it is the second project \u2013 the Elevation Dock project being the first<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.npr.org/2012/02/11/146738529/kickstarter-crowns-a-millionaire | title  = Project Funded Online Hits $1 Million Milestone | date = 2012-02-11 | accessdate = 2012-12-13 | publisher = [[NPR]] }}</ref> \u2013 to achieve more than $1 million in funding through Kickstarter.<ref name=\"cnn\"/> The Double Fine project passed the $2 million mark on February 20, 2012, twelve days after fund raising began.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.pcgamer.com/2012/02/20/double-fine-adventure-game-donations-pass-2-million-22-days-to-go/ | title = Double Fine adventure game donations pass $2 million, 22 days to go | first = Tom | last = Senior | date = 2012-02-20 | accessdate = 2012-02-24 | work = [[PC Gamer]] }}</ref> The Kickstarter closed on March 13 with more than $3.3 million from over 87,000 backers, and with another $110,000 promised by premium backers such as [[Days of Wonder]] and [[Alex Rigopulos]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/165561/Double_Fines_recordbreaking_Kickstarter_closes_with_333M_earned.php | title = Double Fine's record-breaking Kickstarter closes with $3.33M earned  | first = Tom | last = Curtis | date = 2012-03-13 | accessdate = 2012-03-13 | publisher = [[Gamasutra]] }}</ref> Schafer stated that the total funding was nearly the same as the budget for their previous downloadable titles, ''[[Costume Quest]]'' and ''[[Stacking (video game)|Stacking]]'',<ref name=\"eurogamer gdc\">{{cite web | url = http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2012-03-07-schafer-double-fine-adventure-is-a-chinchilla-based-snuff-game | title = Schafer: Double Fine Adventure is a \"chinchilla-based snuff game\" | first = Fred | last = Dutton | date = 2012-03-07 | accessdate = 2012-03-07 | publisher = [[Eurogamer]] }}</ref> as well as his earlier LucasArts game, ''Grim Fandango''.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://arstechnica.com/gaming/news/2012/03/double-fines-adventure-game-kickstarter-ends-with-over-32-million-pledged.ars | title = Double Fine's adventure game Kickstarter ends with over $3.2 million pledged | first = Kyle | last= Orland | date = 2012-03-13 | accessdate = 2012-03-14 | publisher = Ars Technica }}</ref>\n\nThe Kickstarter page was updated with the promise that additional funds would go to increased production values for the game and film, and deployment on additional platforms.<ref name=\"kickstarter\"/><ref name=\"usatoday 1m\"/> A later update by Schafer affirmed that the additional funding will support development for the [[Mac OS X]] and [[Linux]] platforms and select [[iOS]] and [[Android (operating system)|Android]] devices. Additionally, the game will have voice acting for the English version, and include text localization for French, German, Italian, and Spanish languages. Schafer also stated that a [[digital rights management]]-free version of the game will be available after release.<ref>{{cite web | url  =http://kotaku.com/5885523/double-fines-adventure-game-will-be-drm+free-on-pc-mac--mobile  | title = Double Fine's Adventure Game Will be DRM-Free, Available on PC, Mac & Mobile | first = Luke | last = Plunkett | date = 2012-02-15 | accessdate = 2012-02-15 | publisher = Kotaku }}</ref> With the added funding for better production values, Schafer estimated it would likely take about a year to complete the game, missing their original anticipated October 2012 release.<ref name=\"eurogamer gdc\"/> A release in the second quarter of 2013 has been estimated by Double Fine,<ref name=\"lua\"/> later delayed to September 2013.<ref name=\"Turi\">{{cite web | url = http://www.gameinformer.com/games/broken_age/b/pc/archive/2013/04/26/double-fine-breaks-tradition-with-a-modern-adventure.aspx | title =  Broken Age: Double Fine Breaks Tradition With A Modern Adventure | first = Tim | last = Turi | date = 2013-04-26 | accessdate = 2013-05-06 | publisher = [[Game Informer]] }}</ref> At the 2013 [[D.I.C.E. Summit]], Double Fine and [[Ouya]] announced a partnership, assuring that the Ouya console would be the only gaming console for which ''Double Fine Adventure'' would be released on at its launch, in addition to versions for the personal computers.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.joystiq.com/2013/02/06/ouya-partners-with-double-fine-and-words-with-friends-creator/ | title = Ouya partners with Double Fine and 'Words With Friends' creator | first = Alexander | last = Sliwinski | date = 2013-02-06 | accessdate = 2013-02-06 | publisher = Joystiq | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20130208040509/http://www.joystiq.com/2013/02/06/ouya-partners-with-double-fine-and-words-with-friends-creator/ | archive-date = 2013-02-08 | url-status = dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.mcvuk.com/news/read/double-fine-adventure-exclusive-to-ouya-at-launch/0110537 | title = Double Fine Adventure exclusive to Ouya at launch | first = James | last = Batchelor | date = 2013-02-07 | accessdate = 2013-04-22 | publisher = [[MCV (magazine)|MCV]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20130211140700/http://www.mcvuk.com/news/read/double-fine-adventure-exclusive-to-ouya-at-launch/0110537# | archive-date = 2013-02-11 | url-status = dead }}</ref>\n\nAfter the Kickstarter, Double Fine launched a \"slacker backer\" program, which would allow players to pre-order the game through their site at a fixed cost, giving them access to the documentary and beta versions of the game once they were released.<ref name=\"polygon name\"/> The slacker backer option was also offered as part of the Double Fine [[Humble Bundle]] in May 2013 for those that purchased the bundle at a fixed price tier.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.polygon.com/2013/5/7/4305926/double-fine-humble-bundle-brutal-legend-psychonauts-mac-linux-pc | title = Double Fine Humble Bundle brings Brutal Legend, Costume Quest and more to Windows, Mac and Linux | publisher = [[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] | date = 2013-05-07 | accessdate = 2013-05-07 | first = Michael | last = McWhertor }}</ref>\n\n===Game development===\n''Broken Age'' began development under the codename \"Reds\", after Red's Place, following a Double Fine tradition of basing codenames on local [[Chinatown, San Francisco|Chinatown]] bars.<ref>{{cite episode |series=Double Fine Adventure! |number=3 |title=Codename: Reds |date=2012-06-27 |time=23:05 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=a_R2qKHdJlc&t=1385 |access-date=2015-12-26 |publisher=Double Fine Productions}}</ref> As Schafer had not written anything by the time development started, early efforts focused on creating a [[game engine]], art style, and answering technical questions. The [[open-source software|open-source]] [[Moai (software)|Moai game platform]] was chosen as the foundation for the game's engine. Nathan Martz, the technical director for Double Fine, stated that the open source nature of Moai allowed them to easily alter any aspect of the code base, while also supporting all of the targeted platforms.<ref name=\"lua\">{{cite web |url=http://gamasutra.com/view/news/169585/Double_Fines_Kickstarterfunded_adventure_game_to_use_the_Luabased_Moai_platform.php |title=Double Fine's Kickstarter-funded adventure game to use the Lua-based Moai platform |first=Tom |last=Curtis |date=2012-05-01 |access-date=2012-05-01 |publisher=[[Gamasutra]]}}</ref>\n\nProgrammers created a test game involving a red robot, while the artists created a mock-up test scenario to establish an art and animation style inspired by the fine art illustrations of lead artist Nathan Stapley, as well as to work out answers to basic interface questions. A sequence involving an unnamed lumberjack character and a cabin in the woods was created and the team decided to use a system of skeletal animation using segmented 2D characters. Once Schafer had established the basic storyline, involving the intersecting stories of a boy in a sci-fi world and a girl in a fantasy world, concept artists were gathered for an \"art jam\" to brainstorm and produce concept art for the game's creatures and locations. Schafer also asked the community for ideas, several of which were then illustrated by the concept artists.<ref>{{cite web |last=Schafer |first=Tim |title=Writing Update #3: Let's brainstorm Locations together! |url=http://www.doublefine.com/forums/viewthread/7054/ |work=Double Fine Action Forums |publisher=Double Fine Productions |access-date=1 June 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130808092237/http://www.doublefine.com/forums/viewthread/7054# |archive-date=2013-08-08 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nSchafer re-evaluated the state of the project in July 2013 and recognized that at their current rate, they would not be able to complete the game until 2015. For the first time in the company's history Double Fine decided to enlist the help of an outside studio, hiring SuperGenius to assist with art and animation.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://supergeniusstudio.com/project/broken-age/ |title=Broken Age |date=2014 |access-date=2015-12-26 |publisher=SuperGenius}}</ref> Double Fine also realized that they would run out of the Kickstarter funds before 2015, either requiring them to drastically cut back on the project or alter their release plans. Schafer opted to adjust the schedule and split the game into two acts, allowing them to fund the second act with money made from sales of the first.<ref>{{cite episode |series=Double Fine Adventure! |number=10 |title=Part One of Something Great |date=2013-07-02 |time=26:59 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RG5e6B5MHak&t=1619 |access-date=2016-01-01 |publisher=Double Fine Productions}}</ref> They had noticed that breaking the game into halves would fit naturally with events already occurring at the midpoint of the story, making the split relatively simple from a production perspective.<ref name=\"gi afterwords\">{{cite web |url=http://www.gameinformer.com/b/features/archive/2015/06/25/afterwords-broken-age.aspx |title=Afterwords \u2013 Broken Age In Retrospect With Tim Schafer |first=Ben |last=Hanson |date=2015-06-25 |access-date=2015-06-25 |work=[[Game Informer]]}}</ref>\n\nThe first playable version of the game was released on [[Steam (software)|Steam]]'s Early Access platform in January 2014, allowing Double Fine to obtain revenue from sales to fund the remaining development while gaining additional testing input before releasing a final version of the first act. Initial backlash to this announcement led Schafer to clarify that they were not asking for more money to develop the title, and that \"we are using our own money to deliver a bigger game than we Kickstarted\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.computerandvideogames.com/417616/double-fine-not-asking-for-more-money-stresses-schafer/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130706003512/http://www.computerandvideogames.com/417616/double-fine-not-asking-for-more-money-stresses-schafer/ |title=Double Fine 'not asking for more money,' stresses Schafer |first=Mike |last=Jackson |date=2013-07-03 |archive-date=2013-07-06 |access-date=2013-07-03 |work=[[Computer and Video Games]]}}</ref> In the end, the first act was deemed complete and polished enough to graduate from Early Access on January 28, with the second half to be released as a free update later in the year. By February 2014, Schafer confirmed that they had obtained enough from sales of Act 1 to complete the development and release of Act 2.<ref name=GISales>{{Cite web |url=http://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2014-02-21-tim-schafer-how-to-stay-afloat-in-a-pool-of-internet-twitter-hate |title=Schafer: How to stay afloat in \"a pool of Internet Twitter hate\" |first=Brendan |last=Sinclair |date=2014-02-21 |access-date=2014-02-21 |publisher=[[GamesIndustry.biz]]}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2014, producer Greg Rice announced that Schafer had finished writing the second act and the game's finale.<ref name=\"DFP 2014-10-23\">{{cite web |url=http://steamcommunity.com/app/232790/discussions/0/619569341079933147/ |title=Project Update-10/23/2014 |last=Rice |first=Greg |date=2014-10-23 |website=[[Steam (software)|Steam Community]] |publisher=[[Double Fine Productions]] |access-date=2014-11-13}}</ref> Though the second act was anticipated to be released in 2014, Schafer announced in November 2014 that they needed additional time to ensure the quality of Act 2 met expectations and pushed the release back to early 2015.<ref name=\"act2 delay 2015\">{{cite web |url=http://www.polygon.com/2014/11/30/7309373/broken-age-act-two-delayed |title=Broken Age's second act now aiming for early 2015 launch |first=Owne |last=Good |publisher=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] |date=2014-11-30 |access-date=2014-11-30}}</ref> Double Fine was able to use feedback from the first act's release to improve and alter some aspects of the second. One complaint of the first act was the simple nature of its puzzles, whose difficulty Double Fine increased for Act 2. The team also included a nod to a fan theory that had grown regarding the relation between Shay and Alex as a running joke in the second act.<ref name=\"gi afterwords\"/> The game's finale was planned out from the start, before the game was split into Acts; Schafer said he had taken influence of the end credits of ''[[My Neighbor Totoro]]'', which provides epilogue in the form of simple drawings alongside the running credits, to tell the fate of all the characters. He preferred this so that the narrative end of the game before the credits could be focused solely on Vella and Shay, instead of having each character appears to speak a line or so as to explain their fate.<ref name=\"gi afterwords\"/>\n\nA retail version of the game, containing both acts, for Windows, OS X, and Linux platforms will be published through partnership with [[Nordic Games GmbH|Nordic Games]], who had helped to bring retail releases of Double Fine's earlier games in 2014. The retail version will be released near the release of Act 2 for other platforms.<ref name=\"retail\"/> [[Limited Run Games]] will publish retail editions for the [[PlayStation 4]] and [[PlayStation Vita]] in June 2017.<ref>{{Cite web | url = http://kotaku.com/1795501738 | title = Broken Age - Limited Run Games | first = Mike | last = Fahey | date = May 23, 2017 | accessdate = May 24, 2017 | work = [[Kotaku]] }}</ref>\n\nSeveral voice actors who worked on previous Double Fine games voiced characters within ''Broken Age'', including [[Jennifer Hale]], [[Richard Horvitz]], [[Nick Jameson]], [[Nicki Rapp]], Ginny Westcott, and [[Jack Black]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gameinformer.com/games/broken_age/b/pc/archive/2013/09/01/jack-black-joins-the-vocal-cast-of-double-fine-39-s-broken-age.aspx |title=Jack Black Joins The Voice Cast Of Double Fine's Broken Age |first=Kyle |last=Hillard |date=2013-09-01 |access-date=2013-09-02 |work=[[Game Informer]]}}</ref> Other voice actors include [[Elijah Wood]], [[Pendleton Ward]], [[Wil Wheaton]], and [[Masasa Moyo]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gameinformer.com/b/news/archive/2013/11/03/adventure-time-creator-lending-his-voice-to-double-fine-39-s-broken-age.aspx |title=Adventure Time Creator Lending His Voice To Double Fine's Broken Age |first=Kyle |last=Hillard |date=2013-11-03 |access-date=2013-11-03 |work=[[Game Informer]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.polygon.com/2013/12/7/5186620/elijah-wood-broken-age-vgx-2013 |title=Elijah Wood joins the cast of Broken Age as Shay |first=Megan |last=Farokhmanesh |date=2013-12-07 |access-date=2013-12-07 |publisher=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]}}</ref> [[Alex Rigopulos]], the largest backer of the Kickstarter campaign, voiced a character that was designed in his likeness;<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gameinformer.com/games/broken_age/b/pc/archive/2013/12/05/wil-wheaton-leads-impressive-broken-age-voice-cast.aspx |title=Broken Age |first=Matt |last=Helgeson |date=2013-12-05 |access-date=2013-12-05 |work=[[Game Informer]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131209080108/http://www.gameinformer.com/games/broken_age/b/pc/archive/2013/12/05/wil-wheaton-leads-impressive-broken-age-voice-cast.aspx# |archive-date=2013-12-09 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Schafer decided to make the character effectively the same person Rigopulos was in both manner and appearance to minimize the amount of voice acting Rigopulos would need to do.<ref name=\"gi afterwords\"/> [[Days of Wonder]] was the second-largest backer, and through them, Double Fine included the character of the conductor from Days of Wonder's ''[[Ticket to Ride (board game)|Ticket to Ride]]'' games as part of one of Shay's mission rooms.<ref name=\"gi afterwords\"/>\n\n[[Peter McConnell]], who had worked with Schafer on many of his previous games, composed the music for ''Broken Age''. Initially McConnell planned to use only a small ensemble for the musical score but, as the game development progressed, he realized some parts needed a bigger orchestral sound.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://minnesota.publicradio.org/display/web/2014/02/13/peter-mcconnell-broken-age-on-top-score |title=Peter McConnell and Broken Age on Top Score |last=Reese |first=Emily |publisher=Minnesota Public Radio |date=2014-02-13 |access-date=2014-07-15}}</ref> The score was ultimately recorded by wind and string ensembles in San Francisco and the [[Melbourne Symphony Orchestra]], with McConnell overseeing the latter recording session with mixer [[Jory Prum]] remotely from [[Fairfax, California|Fairfax]], California.<ref name=\"polygon-mcconnell\">{{cite web |url=http://www.polygon.com/2014/1/17/5318754/broken-age-score-peter-mcconnell-release-date |title=Psychonauts, Grim Fandango composer wrote Broken Age score |last=Sarkar |first=Samit |publisher=Polygon |date=2014-01-17 |access-date=2014-07-15}}</ref> The score for the first act was released as a soundtrack album on the same day the first half of the game became publicly available.<ref name=\"polygon-mcconnell\"/> The soundtrack was released on vinyl in September 2016.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Cork|first1=James|title=Iam8bit Releasing Limited-Edition Psychonauts, Broken Age Vinyl At PAX|url=http://www.gameinformer.com/b/news/archive/2016/08/26/iam8bit-releasing-limited-edition-psychonauts-broken-age-vinyl-at-pax.aspx|accessdate=2016-09-09|work=Game Informer|date=2016-08-26}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[Electronic Entertainment Expo 2018]], Schafer announced that ''Broken Age'' will be available on the Switch later that year, alongside the remastered version of ''Grim Fandango''.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.usgamer.net/articles/double-fines-grim-fandango-and-broken-age-head-to-nintendo-switch | title = Double Fine's Grim Fandango and Broken Age Head to Nintendo Switch | first=  Jake | last = Green | date = June 13, 2018 | accessdate = June 13, 2018 | work = [[USGamer]] }}</ref>\n\n===Documentary===\nThe development process of ''Broken Age'' was recorded by 2 Player Productions as part of the Kickstarter project. In 2011, Paul Owens of 2 Player Productions wrote an e-mail to Greg Rice and Tim Schafer of Double Fine Productions with a proposition of making a documentary series charting the development of a game from beginning to end. A part of the Kickstarter money was set aside for the documentary.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Dineen|first1=Declan|title=Double Fine Adventure is the best video game documentary to date|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2015-07-29-double-fine-adventure-is-the-greatest-video-game-documentary-to-date|website=[[Eurogamer]]|publisher=Gamer Network|accessdate=2015-07-31|date=2015-07-30}}</ref> The documentary was originally only available to backers, but as of March 2015, the company has started providing the episodes free of charge to YouTube.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.vg247.com/2015/03/04/double-fine-adventure-kickstarter-documentary-releasing-free-on-youtube/ | title = Double Fine Adventure Kickstarter documentary releasing free on YouTube | first = Brenna | last = Hillier | date = 2015-03-03 | accessdate = 2015-03-03 | publisher = [[VG247]] }}</ref> The documentary has received praise for being an honest, open look into the game's development process.<ref>http://au.ign.com/articles/2015/03/27/this-incredible-broken-age-documentary-is-now-free</ref><ref>https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2015/07/20/the-final-episode-of-double-fine-adventure-is-out/#more-302713</ref><ref>http://kotaku.com/if-you-care-about-how-video-games-are-made-watch-the-d-1759216480</ref><ref>https://www.destructoid.com/the-wonderful-double-fine-adventure-documentary-is-going-free-288530.phtml</ref><ref>https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2015/03/double-fine-adventure-documentary-shows-the-woes-o.html</ref><ref>https://arstechnica.com/gaming/2015/10/broken-ages-making-of-documentary-may-be-double-fines-most-enduring-legacy/</ref><ref>http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2015-07-29-double-fine-adventure-is-the-greatest-video-game-documentary-to-date</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n{{Video game reviews\n| title = \n| MC = PC: 76/100<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/broken-age |title=Broken Age for PC Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=2018-07-26}}</ref><br />(Act 1) PC: 82/100<ref name=\"MCPCA1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/broken-age-act-1 |title=Broken Age: Act 1 for PC Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=2018-07-26}}</ref><br />(Act 1) iOS: 76/100<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/ios/broken-age-act-1 |title=Broken Age: Act 1 for iPhone/iPad Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=2018-07-26}}</ref><br />(Act 2) PC: 73/100<ref name=\"MCPCA2\">{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/broken-age-act-2 |title=Broken Age: Act 2 for PC Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=2018-07-26}}</ref><br />PS4: 81/100<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/playstation-4/broken-age |title=Broken Age for PlayStation 4 Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=2018-07-26}}</ref><br />VITA: 90/100<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/playstation-vita/broken-age |title=Broken Age for PlayStation Vita Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=2018-07-26}}</ref><br />XONE: 78/100<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/xbox-one/broken-age |title=Broken Age for Xbox One Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=2018-07-26}}</ref>\n| Destruct = 9.5/10<ref name=DtoidRev1>{{Cite web | url = http://www.destructoid.com/review-broken-age-act-1-269349.phtml | title = Broken Age Act 1 | publisher = [[Destructoid]] | accessdate = 2014-02-01 }}</ref>\n| EuroG = 7/10<ref name=EuroRev1>{{cite web | url = http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2014-01-16-broken-age-act-1-review | title = Broken Age Act 1 review | first = Dan | last = Whitehead | date= 2014-01-16 | accessdate = 2014-01-16 | publisher = [[Eurogamer]]}}</ref>\n| GI = 8/10<ref name=GIRev1>{{cite web | url = http://www.gameinformer.com/games/broken_age/b/pc/archive/2014/01/14/broken-age-act-i-review.aspx | title = Broken Age Act 1 review | first = Jeff | last = Cork | date = 2014-01-14 | accessdate = 2014-01-16 | work = [[Game Informer]] }}</ref>\n| GSpot = 7/10<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.gamespot.com/reviews/broken-age-act-i-review/1900-6415631/ |title=Broken Age Act I Review| first = Maxwell | last = McGee | date = 2014-01-15 | accessdate = 2014-12-07 | work = [[GameSpot]]}}</ref>\n| IGN = 9.5/10<ref name=IGNRev1>{{cite web | url = http://www.ign.com/articles/2014/01/16/broken-age-act-i-review | title = Broken Age, Act 1 | first = Marty | last = Sliva | date = 2014-01-16 | accessdate = 2014-01-16 | publisher = [[IGN]] }}</ref>\n| Poly = 9/10<ref name=PolyRev1>{{cite web | url = http://www.polygon.com/2014/1/15/5309804/broken-age-review | title = Broken Age Act 1 | first = Justin | last= McElroy | date = 2014-01-15 | accessdate = 2014-01-16 | publisher = [[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] }}</ref>\n| rev1 = ''[[TouchArcade]]''\n| rev1Score = iOS: {{rating|3|5}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://toucharcade.com/2014/06/17/broken-age-part-1-review/ |title='Broken Age' Part 1 Review \u2013 An Uneven Split |last=Dotson |first=Carter |date=2014-06-17 |website=[[TouchArcade]] |accessdate=2018-07-26}}</ref>\n}}\n\nThe game's first act was well received by critics, scoring 82/100 on [[review aggregation]] website [[Metacritic]].<ref name=\"MCPCA1\" /> [[Adam Sessler]] of [[Rev3games|Rev3Games]] gave ''Broken Age'' Act 1 a 4/5 calling it a beautiful game with wonderful and funny writing.<ref>{{cite web|last=Sessler|first=Adam|title=Broken Age (Part 1) REVIEW! Adam Sessler Reviews|url=http://revision3.com/rev3gamesreviews/broken-age-1-review|work=Rev3Games|publisher=Revision3|accessdate=28 February 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140203125922/http://revision3.com/rev3gamesreviews/broken-age-1-review#|archive-date=2014-02-03|url-status=dead}}</ref> [[Justin McElroy]], writing at [[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] highlighted the game's characters as \"grounded while approaching absurdity and adversity with brave, heartfelt sincerity\" giving the game a \"kind of depth that's so often lacking in other 'funny' games\".<ref name=PolyRev1/> Within a month of the first act's release, Schafer confirmed that its sales would be sufficient to cover the remaining development costs for Act 2.<ref name=GISales/>\n\nAct 2, released more than a year later, received a similar response overall, with a Metacritic score of 73/100.<ref name=\"MCPCA2\"/> Despite this, many critics saw the second act as a letdown following the success of the first: John Walker of [[Rock Paper Shotgun]] praised the art and voice acting, but criticised Act 2 for its re-use of locations from Act 1 and lackluster ending,<ref name=\"RPSAct2review\">{{Cite web | url = https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2015/04/27/broken-age-act-2-review/#more-281815 | accessdate = 2016-07-19 | title = Wot I Think: Broken Age Act 2 | publisher = [[Rock Paper Shotgun]] | author = John Walker}}</ref> following up his review with a lengthy article expanding on his criticism of the story.<ref name=\"RPSAct2article\">{{Cite web | url = https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2015/04/29/broken-age-plot/ | title = Why Broken Age Act 2's Story Is An Awful Mess | accessdate=2016-07-19 | publisher=[[Rock Paper Shotgun]] | author = John Walker}}</ref> Other critics had similar complaints,<ref name=\"DSAct2review\">{{Cite web | url = http://www.digitalspy.com/gaming/review/a644942/broken-age-act-2-review-a-surprisingly-mishandled-finale/ | title = Broken Age Act 2 review: A surprisingly mishandled finale | author = Scott Nichols | publisher = [[Digital Spy]] | accessdate = 2016-07-19 }}</ref><ref name = PCWorldAct2review>{{Cite web | url = http://www.pcworld.com/article/2921481/broken-age-act-two-review-wasted-potential.html | title = Broken Age (Act Two) review: Wasted potential | accessdate = 2016-07-19 | publisher = [[PC World]] | author = Hayden Dingman }}</ref> including Justin McElroy, who in an update to his initial Act 1 review, was disappointed by too much puzzling in the second half.<ref name=PolyRev1/> He also echoed a common criticism of the frustrating difficulty of the puzzles, which many reviewers felt were much harder than in Act 1, especially if players tried to pick it up without replaying the first half.<ref name=\"RPSAct2review\" /><ref name = DSAct2review /><ref name=\"KotakuAct2review\">{{Cite web | url = http://kotaku.com/the-final-part-of-broken-age-is-a-bittersweet-ending-to-1700440814 | accessdate=2016-07-19 | title = The Final Part of Broken Age Is a Bittersweet Ending to a Great Game | author = Evan Narcisse | publisher = [[Kotaku]] }}</ref>\n\n===Impact===\n{{see also|Crowdfunding in video games}}\nThe success of the fund-raising campaign established crowd-sourcing as a challenge to publisher funding (and control) for multimillion-dollar projects. [[John Walker (journalist)|John Walker]] from [[Rock, Paper, Shotgun]] was quick to point out that this doesn't pose a major threat to publishers on a large scale, but added that it would force publishers to ask themselves questions such as \"Are we really in touch with our audience\u2019s desires?\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2012/02/09/thought-double-fines-kickstarter-asks-some-big-questions/ |title=Thought: Double Fine's Kickstarter Asks Big Questions |publisher=Rock, Paper, Shotgun | first = John | last = Walker|date=2012-02-09 |accessdate=2012-02-10}}</ref> Johnny Cullen of [[VG247]] compared the Double Fine Kickstarter to the release of [[Radiohead]]'s album ''[[In Rainbows]]'', which the band had sold through their website in a [[pay-what-you-want]] model prior to a physical printing, without the interference of a music publisher. Cullen noted the model of crowd-sourcing has previously not worked for some game developers, and does not expect it to be a guaranteed success for future efforts, as he believes Double Fine is a unique studio with a dedicated fan base, aspects that are not shared by all developers.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.vg247.com/2012/02/09/double-fines-kickstart-provides-a-radiohead-moment/ | title = Double Fine's Kickstarter provides a Radiohead moment | publisher = [[VG247]] | first = Johnny | last = Cullen | date = 2012-02-09 | accessdate = 2012-02-09 }}</ref>\n\nInitial commentary largely framed Double Fine as exceptional, citing Double Fine's reputation,<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.edge-online.com/features/devs-celebrate-double-fines-kickstarter-success | title = Devs celebrate Double Fine's Kickstarter success | date = 2012-02-10 | accessdate = 2012-02-10 | work = [[Edge (magazine)|Edge]] }}</ref> experience with the under-serviced genre,<ref>{{cite web | url = http://kotaku.com/5883864/why-the-internet-gave-this-video-game-1-million-in-a-single-day | title = Why the Internet Gave This Man $1 Million. In a Single Day. | first = Luke | last = Plunkett | date = 2012-02-09 | accessdate = 2012-02-10 | publisher = Kotaku }}</ref> and history of difficulty with publisher funding<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2012-02-15-the-kickstarter-conundrum | title= The Kickstarter Conundrum |  date = 2012-02-15 | accessdate  = 2012-02-15 | publisher = [[Eurogamer]] | first = Dan | last = Whitehead }}</ref> as reasons why Double Fine's case was unique. Initially, many remained skeptical that such a level of success could be replicated.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.giantbomb.com/news/on-kickstarter-there-are-no-guarantees/4055/ | title = On Kickstarter, There Are No Guarantees | first = Patrick | last = Klepek | date = 2012-03-27 | accessdate = 2012-03-28 | publisher = [[Giant Bomb]] }}</ref> Schafer further agreed that the success of the Double Fine Kickstarter would be somewhat difficult to replicate for other games, even for Double Fine, as it would require the project to be \"a good story for people to get behind\".<ref name=\"gb interview\"/>\n\nInitial fears that this success would be isolated were allayed as new projects emerged. As the ''Double Fine Adventure'' campaign closed, [[Brian Fargo]] of [[inXile Entertainment]] launched a Kickstarter to fund development of the sequel ''[[Wasteland 2]]'', which met its target of $900,000 in funding within two days,<ref name=\"Curtis\">{{cite web | url = http://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/40362/Wasteland_creator_looks_to_Kickstarter_for_series_revival.php | title = Wasteland creator looks to Kickstarter for series revival  | first = Tom | last = Curtis | date = 2012-02-16 | accessdate = 2012-02-16 | publisher = [[Gamasutra]] }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.vg247.com/2012/03/14/wasteland-2-kickstarter-raises-over-500k-on-day-one/ | title =  Kickstarter: Schafer closes on $3.3m, Wasteland 2 raises over $500k in one day | first = Dave | last = Oshry | date = 2012-03-14 | accessdate = 2012-03-14 | publisher = [[VG247]] }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/165868/Wasteland_2_Kickstarter_surpasses_900K_goal_in_2_days.php | title = Wasteland 2 Kickstarter surpasses $900K goal in 2 days | first = Mike | last = Rose | date = 2012-03-15 | accessdate = 2012-03-15 | publisher = [[Gamasutra]] }}</ref> and eventually raised more than $2.9 million. ''Double Fine Adventure'' brought in 61,692 new users to Kickstarter, and greatly increased the platform's visibility and viability for funding of games projects.<ref>[http://www.kickstarter.com/blog/blockbuster-effects Blockbuster Effects \u00bb The Kickstarter Blog \u2014 Kickstarter]. Kickstarter.com (2012-03-29). Retrieved on 2014-01-14.</ref> Within the six weeks following the launch of the Double Fine Adventure Kickstarter, the site raised more than $2.9 million in pledges (outside of the Double Fine project) for video game related projects, compared with $1.7 million total for the category in the prior two years, as well as increasing the amount of funding coming into projects of all categories.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/167549/Double_Fine_Kickstarter_brings_huge_boost_to_crowdfunded_games.php | title = \tDouble Fine Kickstarter brings huge boost to crowd-funded games  | first = Tom | last = Curtis | date = 2012-03-29 | accessdate = 2012-03-29 | publisher = [[Gamasutra]] }}</ref> In October, ''[[Project Eternity]]'' surpassed Double Fine's funding record, further suggesting the crowd-funding model will continue to be a part of the gaming landscape.<ref>[http://www.nbcnews.com/technology/ingame/project-eternity-raises-3-9-million-sets-kickstarter-record-1C6522242 'Project Eternity' raises $3.9 million, sets Kickstarter record]. NBC News.com (2012-10-17). Retrieved on 2014-01-14.</ref>\n\nThe success of ''Double Fine Adventure'' has had a particularly visible impact on the adventure genre, inspiring several other established adventure game developers to use Kickstarter as a means to return to the genre.<ref name=\"1UP\">{{cite web |url=http://www.1up.com/features/adventure-game-kickstarter-roundup |title=Your Adventure Game Kickstarter Roundup |last=Mackey |first=Bob |date=12 June 2012 |accessdate=28 August 2013 |publisher=[[1UP.com]] }}</ref> In the months following its release, the creators of ''[[Broken Sword]]'',<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kickstarter.com/projects/revolutionsoftware/broken-sword-the-serpents-curse-adventure |title=Broken Sword - the Serpent's Curse Adventure by Revolution Software \u2014 Kickstarter |publisher=Kickstarter |accessdate= }}</ref> ''[[Gabriel Knight]]'',<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kickstarter.com/projects/1005365109/jane-jensens-pinkerton-road-2012-2013-csg |title=Jane Jensen's Moebius and Pinkerton Road Studio by Jane Jensen \u2014 Kickstarter |publisher=Kickstarter |accessdate= }}</ref> ''[[Leisure Suit Larry]]'',<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kickstarter.com/projects/leisuresuitlarry/make-leisure-suit-larry-come-again |title=Make Leisure Suit Larry come again! by Replay Games \u2014 Kickstarter |publisher=Kickstarter |accessdate= }}</ref> ''[[Space Quest]]''<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kickstarter.com/projects/spaceventure/two-guys-spaceventure-by-the-creators-of-space-que |title=Two Guys SpaceVenture - by the creators of Space Quest by Two Guys From Andromeda \u2014 Kickstarter |publisher=Kickstarter |accessdate= }}</ref> and ''[[Tex Murphy]]''<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kickstarter.com/projects/texmurphy/tex-murphy-project-fedora |title=Tex Murphy - Project Fedora by Chris Jones & Aaron Conners \u2014 Kickstarter |publisher=Kickstarter |accessdate= }}</ref> have all managed to raise amounts in excess of Schafer's original goal of $400,000.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|http://www.brokenagegame.com/}}\n\n{{Tim Schafer}}\n{{Double Fine Productions}}\n{{Portal bar|Video games}}\n\n[[Category:2014 video games]]\n[[Category:2015 video games]]\n[[Category:Android (operating system) games]]\n[[Category:Coming-of-age fiction]]\n[[Category:Double Fine Productions]]\n[[Category:Episodic video games]]\n[[Category:IOS games]]\n[[Category:Kickstarter-funded video games]]\n[[Category:Linux games]]\n[[Category:Lua-scripted video games]]\n[[Category:MacOS games]]\n[[Category:Nintendo Switch games]]\n[[Category:Ouya games]]\n[[Category:PlayStation 4 games]]\n[[Category:PlayStation Network games]]\n[[Category:PlayStation Vita games]]\n[[Category:Point-and-click adventure games]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in the United States]]\n[[Category:Video games scored by Peter McConnell]]\n[[Category:Video games featuring female protagonists]]\n[[Category:Windows games]]\n[[Category:Xbox One games]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox video game\n| title = Broken Age\n| image = File:Broken Age cover art.jpg\n| developer = [[Double Fine Productions]]\n| publisher = Double Fine Productions\n| caption = Cover art featuring Vella (left) who is to be sacrificed to protect her home village from a giant monster, and Shay (right) who appears to be the only passenger on a spacecraft monitored by an overly motherly computer.\n| director = [[Tim Schafer]]\n| producer = Greg Rice\n| designer = \n| programmer = Oliver Franzke<br />Anna Kipnis\n| artist = Lee Petty<br />[[Nathan Stapley]]\n| writer = Tim Schafer\n| composer = [[Peter McConnell]]\n| engine = [[Moai (software)|Moai]]\n| platforms = [[Microsoft Windows]], [[OS X]], [[Linux]], [[Ouya]], [[iOS]], [[Android (operating system)|Android]], [[PlayStation 4]], [[PlayStation Vita]], [[Xbox One]], [[Nintendo Switch]]\n| released = {{Collapsible list\n  |title = April 28, 2015\n  |titlestyle = font-weight:normal;background:transparent;text-align:left\n  |'''''Act 1'''''<br />'''Windows''', '''OS X''', '''Linux'''<br />January 14, 2014 <small>(Backer Beta)</small><ref name=\"polygonouya\">{{cite web |url=http://www.polygon.com/2013/2/6/3961578/double-fine-adventure-the-cave-ouya-dice-2013 |publisher=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] |title=Double Fine Adventure and The Cave coming to Ouya |date=2013-02-06 |accessdate=2013-07-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=First act of Broken Age coming to Steam in January|url=http://www.gamesradar.com/first-act-broken-age-coming-steam-january/|work=GamesRadar|accessdate=11 December 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2014-01-10-broken-age-episode-one-comes-to-early-access-on-tuesday | title = Broken Age Episode One comes to Early Access on Tuesday | publisher = [[Eurogamer]] | first = Jeffrey | last = Mutelef | date = 2014-01-10 | accessdate = 2014-01-10 }}</ref><br />January 28, 2014 <small>(Public)</small><ref>http://store.steampowered.com/app/232790/</ref><br />'''Ouya'''<br />May 30, 2014<br />'''iOS'''<br />June 12, 2014<br />'''Android'''<br />April 28, 2015<br />'''PS4''', '''PS Vita'''<br />{{vgrelease|NA|April 28, 2015<ref name=\"Act2\"/>|EU|April 29, 2015<ref name=\"Act2\"/>}}\n  |'''''Act 2'''''<br />{{vgrelease|NA|April 28, 2015<ref name=\"Act2\"/>|EU|April 29, 2015<ref name=\"Act2\">{{cite web|last1=Silva|first1=Marty|title=Broken Age Act 2 release date announced|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2015/03/25/broken-age-act-2-release-date-announced|website=IGN|accessdate=March 25, 2015|date=March 25, 2015}}</ref>}}\n  }}\n| genre = [[Point-and-click adventure]] \n| modes = [[Single-player video game|Single-player]]\n}}\n\n'''''Broken Age''''' is a [[point-and-click adventure]] [[video game]] developed and published by [[Double Fine]].<ref name=\"polygon name\">{{cite web | url = http://www.polygon.com/2013/3/24/4141386/double-fine-adventure- | title = Broken Age is the official title of Double Fine Adventure | first = Alexa Ray | last = Corriea | publisher = [[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] | date = 2013-03-24 | accessdate = 2013-03-24 }}</ref> ''Broken Age'' was game director [[Tim Schafer]]'s first return to the genre since 1998's ''[[Grim Fandango]]'', and was released for [[Microsoft Windows]], [[Mac OS X]], [[Linux]], [[iOS]], [[Android (operating system)|Android]], [[PlayStation 4]], [[PlayStation Vita]], and [[Xbox One]] platforms. The game was developed in two acts; the first was released on January 28, 2014 (two weeks earlier for Kickstarter backers), and the second was released on April 28, 2015. A retail version of the complete game for Windows, OS X, and Linux, published by [[Nordic Games GmbH|Nordic Games]], was released on April 28, 2015.<ref name=\"retail\">{{cite web | title = Broken Age is out now | url = http://www.nordicgames.at/index.php/article/broken_age_is_out_now | publisher = [[Nordic Games GmbH|Nordic Games]] | date = 2015-04-28 | accessdate = 2015-04-29 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150502074846/http://www.nordicgames.at/index.php/article/broken_age_is_out_now | archive-date = 2015-05-02 | url-status = dead }}</ref> A [[Nintendo Switch]] version was released on September 13, 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nintendoeverything.com/broken-age-sees-surprise-release-on-switch/|title=Broken Age sees surprise release on Switch|last=Richards|first=Brian|date=2018-09-13|work=Nintendo Life|accessdate=2019-03-23}}</ref>\n\n''Broken Age'' began under the working title ''Double Fine Adventure'' as a [[Kickstarter]] [[crowdfunding|crowd-funded]] project promoted by Double Fine and [[2 Player Productions]] in February 2012. Though originally a goal of only $400,000 was set to cover the costs of development and documentary filming, ''Broken Age'' became the largest crowd-funded video game project at the time, raising over 3.45 million dollars from more than 87,000 backers within the month. It remains one of [[List of highest funded crowdfunding projects|the highest-backed crowd-funded projects]] of any type, and its success helped to establish [[crowdfunding in video games|Kickstarter and other crowd-funding mechanisms]] as a viable alternative to traditional [[venture capital]] and [[video game publisher|publisher]] funding for niche video game titles. The game's development was chronicled by an episodic series of documentaries produced by 2 Player Productions.\n\n==Gameplay==\n''Broken Age'' is a [[point-and-click adventure game]], where the player-controlled character can be directed to move about the screen, examine objects, and talk to non-player characters to learn more about the game world. The game features two playable characters, each located in seemingly separate worlds; the player can switch from one character to the other via the game's interface at any time, but otherwise these characters do not interact in any direct way. The game employs context-sensitive actions instead of using verb lists as early adventure games would use, as Schafer stated that in essence, \"there really was always one verb, which was 'interact with'\" and opted for the more modern approach.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.polygon.com/2013/11/3/5059690/broken-age-preview | title = Broken Age built around context-based interactions, not a list of verbs | publisher = [[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] | date =2013-11-03 | accessdate = 2013-11-03 | first  = Megan | last =  Farokhmanesh  }}</ref> Each character has separate item inventories as they collect objects; items can then be used by dragging them onto context-sensitive areas on the screen or combined with other inventory items.\n\n==Plot==\n===Act 1===\n''Broken Age'' tells the story of two teenagers with no immediately apparent connection, each \"seeking to break the tradition in their lives\".<ref name=\"polygon name\"/>\n\nVella Tartine (voiced by [[Masasa Moyo]]) is a young woman living in the Badlands, a land ravaged by the Mogs, giant creatures that come from beyond a wall called the Plague Dam. They are appeased by the sacrifice of young girls at a number of ''Maiden's Feasts'' held at various villages. They appear every fourteen years for those maidens. Vella is chosen to be sacrificed to Mog Chothra at the feast in her hometown of Sugar Bunting (formerly a town made up of warriors named Steel Bunting) but concludes that if the monster could be killed, the rituals could be ended. She finds a way to escape the beast's attack and ends up in Meriloft, a small colony which rests on a cluster of semisolid clouds. They are dealing with the aftermath of their own Feast, affirming her belief that the rites are disastrous to their people and should be ended. She then finds her way to a nearby port town, Shellmound, where they are preparing for their own Feast. There she discovers the Dead Eye God's temple, which turns out to be an ancient spaceship, the Maloruna, half-buried by the sand. She is able to wake its pilot, Alex, from his three hundred year stasis, and he helps her to rig the ship's scanning system to fire a laser at Mog Chothra when he shows up for the Feast. Vella's plan works, and she is able to bring down the creature.\n\nShay Volta (voiced by [[Elijah Wood]]) is a young man and seemingly the only passenger on the spaceship Bossa Nostra (Bassinostra), an \"incubator vessel\". The ship's computer has two [[artificial intelligence]]s (A.I.s). The computer's diurnal A.I., named \"MOM\", acts as a mother figure to Shay, occupying him with infantile \"missions\" and boring routines, while preventing him from learning about or exploring anything farther than the outside of the ship. The computer's nocturnal A.I. acts as a father figure to Shay and is more understanding of Shay's desire for independence, but appears to be too busy to spend time with Shay. The computer asserts that he is part of ''Project Dandelion'', a last-ditch effort by his home planet, Loruna, to protect Shay (the only survivor of his race following the planet's destruction) and try to find a home for him. When Shay sneaks into the bowels of the ship, he finds a stowaway named Marek wearing a wolf costume. Marek claims that, unbeknownst to him, a war rages in the galaxy, and tells Shay that he needs his help to save some innocent creatures who have been imprisoned in different areas of the galaxy as a result. Marek guides Shay through various missions against the computer's knowledge and control, trying to rescue a number of the creatures at each location before their position is discovered by an enemy force. During one of these rescues, Shay refuses to leave the last creature behind, causing the ship to be attacked, and trapping Marek under a pile of debris. In the ensuing chaos, Shay is knocked unconscious.\n\nAct 1 ends when Vella, going up to the downed Mog Chothra, discovers the monster is mechanical. Shay emerges confused from inside, revealing his belief of being in space was merely part of an illusion and he was unwittingly controlling Mog Chothra. Vella attempts to punch Shay but misses and falls into Mog Chothra's mouth. The mouth closes behind her, leaving them both trapped in each other's worlds, uncertain of what to do in their new surroundings.\n\n=== Act 2 ===\nShay, trapped outside Mog Chothra, is reminded that the ship's AIs are actually his real parents; his father, Ray Volta, stuck outside with Shay, warns that his mother is still trapped within. As Ray tries to find a way back inside, Shay, recovered from his shock of the outside world, takes a look around when the ship takes off, stranding them there. Shay meets Alex, learning that he was a previous subject of ''Project Dandelion''. Alex was born on his ship, the Maloruna, a Diamond Age Dandelion Cruiser. His parents never showed him any pictures of Loruna. They lived for about 20 years after the crash (280 years ago), and then died three months apart from each other; their passing was one of the reasons why he went into ''crysolation''. Before his ship's crash, Alex had a talking cello named Marek who told him to hack the controls and rescue innocent creatures, just like Shay, who realizes that they were really capturing girls.\n\nShay offers to help repair Alex's ship to return to Loruna, where Alex believes Shay's ship is heading. Meanwhile, Vella (having accidentally reactivated the computer's autopilot) works her way into the ship and encounters Marek, who is still pinned under debris. Marek directs Vella to get into the control room as to stop Shay's mother, Hope Volta. Vella pretends that she is Shay to trick his mother into opening the door, but they are both quickly locked inside by Marek, who reveals himself to be Marekai, a member of a race called the Thrush. Marekai told Hope their world was dying so she went forth and found salvation, as many have before her: their ships were the Mogs. It turns out that Loruna is not a planet but an empire beyond the Plague Dam. He then directs the ship to deliver Vella there. Meanwhile, Shay makes his way through Shellmound and Meriloft to find parts to repair Alex's ship and go back to Loruna. He retraces Vella's journey and talks to the people with whom she interacted in Act 1 and her family, as they search for her.\n\nBack on Vella's side: Vella frees herself and Hope, and the true nature of ''Project Dandelion'' is revealed: the Thrush, believing the rest of the beings on the planet to be filled with disease, barricaded themselves with the humans whom they govern beyond the Plague Dam, and over the generations, modified their normal human DNA to become \"superior\"; but also lost certain traits necessary for survival. Project Dandelion has been used to send out uniquely attuned human children from their normal human population who could locate a special maiden via the Maiden's Feasts to \"true\" their bloodline. Vella was the one Shay selected amongst the other Maidens (who are alive but held captive), and the Thrush is planning on killing her to incorporate her genetics into theirs.\n\nKnowing her potential fate, Vella creates a bomb from the ship's power core to destroy the hangar where all of the Mog ships are kept. After planting the bomb, Hope and Vella set their ship to escape. Meanwhile, Shay helps Alex reactivate his ship and they set a course directly for the Plague Dam, accompanied by Shay's father and Vella's family. Right outside the gate, the two ships collide and the Thrush starts attacking the ships, which are both stuck on autopilot. Shay and Vella work together to cause Alex's ship reactor to overheat, melting both ships together. Everyone but Shay escapes, and Vella and Hope encourage him to jump to safety; Shay jumps, just missing a ledge, but is saved by the noble sacrifice of one of his robots, Grabbin' Gary. The fused ships soon solidify, forming a bridge between the mainland and the Plague Dam. Shay and Vella finally meet. After a moment's hesitation, they smile at one another.\n\nWithin the credit sequence, it is shown that the Thrush is deposed from power, the Plague Dam is demolished, and the humans of Loruna and the Badlands form a peaceful alliance. Many images in the credits include the notable people, animals, and machines shown throughout the game living much better lives.\n\n==Development==\n\n===Announcement and fund-raising===\n[[File:Double Fine Adventure logo.jpg|thumb|right|Promotional art used to promote the project on Kickstarter, with the Double Fine two-headed baby logo, used as part of the rewards for Kickstarter backers]]\n\n''Double Fine Adventure'' was announced by way of a [[Kickstarter]] project initiated on February 8, 2012. The idea came after Double Fine's [[Tim Schafer]] was interviewed for 2 Player Productions' upcoming Kickstarter-funded documentary on the game ''[[Minecraft]]''.<ref name=\"pcworld 2player\">{{cite web | url = http://www.pcworld.com/article/250101/2_player_productions_interview.html#tk.rss_main | title = 2 Player Productions Interview | first = Dave | last= Daw | date = 2012-02-17 | accessdate= 2012-02-17 | work = [[PC World (magazine)|PC World]] }}</ref> After the interview, Schafer and 2 Player discussed the idea of the production company filming a documentary about Double Fine as a future project.<ref name=\"pcworld 2player\"/> Double Fine had already had experience as a studio being filmed during development of ''[[Psychonauts]]'' for an episode of [[G4 (U.S. TV channel)|G4 TV]]'s ''[[Icons (TV series)|Icons]]'' series.<ref name=\"vb interview\">{{cite web | url = https://venturebeat.com/2012/02/21/double-fines-tim-schafer-on-kickstarter-success-i-did-not-expect-this-interview/ | title = Double Fine's Tim Schafer on Kickstarter success: It can happen again (interview) | publisher = [[Venture Beat]] | date = 2012-02-21 | accessdate = 2012-02-21 | first = Stefanie | last = Fogel }}</ref> When 2 Player completed the ''Minecraft'' project, around November 2011, they wanted to create a more in-depth documentary, recognizing that Double Fine had the right type of environment where such a documentary would be possible.<ref name=\"pcworld 2player\"/> The two studios began to work out the specifics of the project, but Schafer realized that publisher interference would make an honest portrayal of game development impossible. Double Fine lacked the resources to self-fund a game, and 2 Player lacked the ability to fund the film, so the two companies elected to crowd-fund the project on Kickstarter, a method Schafer had seen successfully used to raise much smaller amounts for independent game developers. The creation of a new game was initially considered \"kind of as a sidenote\" by Schafer to accommodate the documentary filming.<ref name=\"kickstarter\"/><ref name=\"gb interview\"/>\n\nThe [[adventure game]] genre was selected to offer the public a product that would not have existed without their support, and help to distinguish the project from the developer's publisher-financed work.<ref name=\"gb interview\">{{cite web | url = http://www.giantbomb.com/news/16-million-and-counting/3981/ |title = $1.6 Million and Counting | first = Patrick | last = Klepek | date = 2012-02-13 | accessdate = 2012-02-13 | publisher = [[Giant Bomb]] }}</ref> Schafer, a veteran of [[LucasArts adventure games|LucasArts]], has long been associated with adventure games, a genre that has long been stigmatized as commercially niche, particularly since the release of Schafer's own ''[[Grim Fandango]]''.<ref name=\"kickstarter\">{{cite web | url = http://www.kickstarter.com/projects/66710809/double-fine-adventure | title = Double Fine Adventure | publisher = [[Double Fine Productions]] | date = 2012-02-08 | accessdate = 2012-02-09 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gilbert|first=Andrew Simon|date=2017|title=Crowdfunding Nostalgia: Kickstarter and the Revival of Classic PC Game Genres|journal=The Computer Games Journal|language=en|volume=6|issue=1\u20132|pages=17\u201332|doi=10.1007/s40869-017-0031-x|issn=2052-773X}}</ref> In his pitch to the public, Schafer argued that funding for such a project would be very difficult to come by, stating \"If I were to go to a publisher right now and pitch an adventure game, they'd laugh in my face.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wired.co.uk/news/archive/2012-02/09/double-fine-kickstarter |title=Tim Schafer persuades fans to finance next adventure game |work=[[Wired UK]] |date=2012-02-09 |accessdate=2012-02-10 |first=Mark |last=Brown |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120212003117/http://www.wired.co.uk/news/archive/2012-02/09/double-fine-kickstarter |archivedate=2012-02-12 }}</ref> Ron Gilbert, another ex-LucasArts adventure game designer at Double Fine, has long expressed this sentiment, writing in his personal blog, \"From first-hand experience, I can tell you that if you even utter the words \"adventure game\" in a meeting with a publisher you can just pack up your spiffy concept art and leave.  You'd get a better reaction by announcing that you have the plague.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://grumpygamer.com/3258434 |title=Adventure Games (via) |date=2005-07-23 |accessdate=2012-02-17 |publisher=[[Ron Gilbert]] |first=Ron |last=Gilbert |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070612160141/http://grumpygamer.com/3258434 |archivedate=2007-06-12 }}</ref>  Schafer explained that the game will not be \"museum\" or \"nostalgia\" work, but instead \"It's going to be fresh and feel modern and feel like what the next game would have been if I'd made one straight after ''Grim Fandango''\".<ref name=\"eurogamer gdc\"/>\n\nThe Kickstarter drive was launched in early February 2012 so that, regardless of its success, Schafer would be able to talk about it during the 2012 [[Game Developers' Conference]] in early March.<ref name=\"gb interview\"/> Double Fine set the goal for the project at $400,000, with $100,000 allocated to the film production and $300,000 for the game. Although this was the largest goal of any gaming project yet on Kickstarter, it was the lowest budget the company had worked with, and a small fraction of the budget of the company's previous downloadable games, which cost around $2 million.<ref name=\"kickstarter\"/><ref name=\"gb interview\"/> Schafer admitted that a game made for this budget would be \"hobbled,\" and that the budget was chosen because it was the absolute minimum he thought he could make an adventure game for.<ref name=\"gb interview\"/> The two had originally envisioned a total $200,000 budget, a typical cost for an [[iOS]] game, but Schafer had doubts about whether Double Fine could deliver a game for such a low cost.<ref name=\"gb interview\"/>\n\nVarious incentives were given to those that pledged $15 or more, including the game itself, early [[beta (software)|beta]] access to the game, access to private community areas to discuss the game, prints, and invitations to meet with the Double Fine staff.<ref name=\"kickstarter\"/> Further rewards were added through a second update two weeks into the effort, including digital soundtracks, physical copies of the game and documentary, and an art book.<ref name=\"eurogamer update2\">{{cite web | url = http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2012-02-24-double-fine-adventure-will-likely-be-old-school-2d | title = Double Fine Adventure will likely be \"old school\" 2D | first = Fred | last = Dutton | date = 2012-02-24 | accessdate= 2012-02-24 | publisher = [[Eurogamer]] }}</ref> In launching the Kickstarter project, Double Fine claimed it was the first major studio to use the model for the funding of a game.<ref name=\"cnn\">{{cite web | url = http://whatsnext.blogs.cnn.com/2012/02/10/when-making-a-game-is-a-game-in-itself/ | title = When making a game is a game in itself | first = John | last = Sutter | date = 2012-02-10 | accessdate = 2012-02-10 | publisher = CNN | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120211221839/http://whatsnext.blogs.cnn.com/2012/02/10/when-making-a-game-is-a-game-in-itself/ | archive-date = 2012-02-11 | url-status = dead }}</ref>\n\nWithin nine hours, the Kickstarter project had exceeded the $400,000 goal.<ref>{{cite web|last=Yin-Poole |first=Wesley |url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2012-02-09-psychonauts-developer-double-fine-making-fan-funded-adventure-game |title=Psychonauts developer Double Fine making fan-funded adventure game |publisher = [[Eurogamer]] |date=2012-02-09 |accessdate=2012-02-09}}</ref> Within 24 hours, it had surpassed $1 million.<ref name=\"usatoday 1m\">{{cite web | url = https://www.usatoday.com/tech/gaming/story/2012-02-09/game-funding-crowdsourced/53031998/1 | title = Video game makers use crowd-sourced funding for new project | first = Mike | last = Snider | date = 2012-02-09 | accessdate = 2012-02-09 | work = [[USA Today]] }}</ref> As the funds raised approached $1.35 million, Schafer noted that the total had already exceeded the budget for ''[[Day of the Tentacle]]'' ($600,000) and was nearing the budget for ''[[Full Throttle (1995 video game)|Full Throttle]]'' ($1.5 million).<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2012-02-10-double-fine-adventure-passes-day-of-the-tentacle-budget | title = Double Fine Adventure passes Day of the Tentacle budget | first = Fred | last = Dutton | date = 2012-02-10 | accessdate = 2012-02-10 | publisher = [[Eurogamer]] }}</ref>  Kickstarter stated on the day after its start that the Double Fine effort is the most successful to date, having attracted more backers than any prior effort in the site's history<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.thestar.com/article/1128741--game-developer-raises-700-000-in-less-than-a-day-using-crowd-funding-site-kickstarter | title = Game developer raises $700,000 in less than a day using crowd-funding site Kickstarter | work = [[Toronto Star]] | date = 2012-02-09 | accessdate = 2012-02-09 | first = Raju | last = Mudhar }}</ref> while others have noted it is the second project \u2013 the Elevation Dock project being the first<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.npr.org/2012/02/11/146738529/kickstarter-crowns-a-millionaire | title  = Project Funded Online Hits $1 Million Milestone | date = 2012-02-11 | accessdate = 2012-12-13 | publisher = [[NPR]] }}</ref> \u2013 to achieve more than $1 million in funding through Kickstarter.<ref name=\"cnn\"/> The Double Fine project passed the $2 million mark on February 20, 2012, twelve days after fund raising began.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.pcgamer.com/2012/02/20/double-fine-adventure-game-donations-pass-2-million-22-days-to-go/ | title = Double Fine adventure game donations pass $2 million, 22 days to go | first = Tom | last = Senior | date = 2012-02-20 | accessdate = 2012-02-24 | work = [[PC Gamer]] }}</ref> The Kickstarter closed on March 13 with more than $3.3 million from over 87,000 backers, and with another $110,000 promised by premium backers such as [[Days of Wonder]] and [[Alex Rigopulos]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/165561/Double_Fines_recordbreaking_Kickstarter_closes_with_333M_earned.php | title = Double Fine's record-breaking Kickstarter closes with $3.33M earned  | first = Tom | last = Curtis | date = 2012-03-13 | accessdate = 2012-03-13 | publisher = [[Gamasutra]] }}</ref> Schafer stated that the total funding was nearly the same as the budget for their previous downloadable titles, ''[[Costume Quest]]'' and ''[[Stacking (video game)|Stacking]]'',<ref name=\"eurogamer gdc\">{{cite web | url = http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2012-03-07-schafer-double-fine-adventure-is-a-chinchilla-based-snuff-game | title = Schafer: Double Fine Adventure is a \"chinchilla-based snuff game\" | first = Fred | last = Dutton | date = 2012-03-07 | accessdate = 2012-03-07 | publisher = [[Eurogamer]] }}</ref> as well as his earlier LucasArts game, ''Grim Fandango''.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://arstechnica.com/gaming/news/2012/03/double-fines-adventure-game-kickstarter-ends-with-over-32-million-pledged.ars | title = Double Fine's adventure game Kickstarter ends with over $3.2 million pledged | first = Kyle | last= Orland | date = 2012-03-13 | accessdate = 2012-03-14 | publisher = Ars Technica }}</ref>\n\nThe Kickstarter page was updated with the promise that additional funds would go to increased production values for the game and film, and deployment on additional platforms.<ref name=\"kickstarter\"/><ref name=\"usatoday 1m\"/> A later update by Schafer affirmed that the additional funding will support development for the [[Mac OS X]] and [[Linux]] platforms and select [[iOS]] and [[Android (operating system)|Android]] devices. Additionally, the game will have voice acting for the English version, and include text localization for French, German, Italian, and Spanish languages. Schafer also stated that a [[digital rights management]]-free version of the game will be available after release.<ref>{{cite web | url  =http://kotaku.com/5885523/double-fines-adventure-game-will-be-drm+free-on-pc-mac--mobile  | title = Double Fine's Adventure Game Will be DRM-Free, Available on PC, Mac & Mobile | first = Luke | last = Plunkett | date = 2012-02-15 | accessdate = 2012-02-15 | publisher = Kotaku }}</ref> With the added funding for better production values, Schafer estimated it would likely take about a year to complete the game, missing their original anticipated October 2012 release.<ref name=\"eurogamer gdc\"/> A release in the second quarter of 2013 has been estimated by Double Fine,<ref name=\"lua\"/> later delayed to September 2013.<ref name=\"Turi\">{{cite web | url = http://www.gameinformer.com/games/broken_age/b/pc/archive/2013/04/26/double-fine-breaks-tradition-with-a-modern-adventure.aspx | title =  Broken Age: Double Fine Breaks Tradition With A Modern Adventure | first = Tim | last = Turi | date = 2013-04-26 | accessdate = 2013-05-06 | publisher = [[Game Informer]] }}</ref> At the 2013 [[D.I.C.E. Summit]], Double Fine and [[Ouya]] announced a partnership, assuring that the Ouya console would be the only gaming console for which ''Double Fine Adventure'' would be released on at its launch, in addition to versions for the personal computers.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.joystiq.com/2013/02/06/ouya-partners-with-double-fine-and-words-with-friends-creator/ | title = Ouya partners with Double Fine and 'Words With Friends' creator | first = Alexander | last = Sliwinski | date = 2013-02-06 | accessdate = 2013-02-06 | publisher = Joystiq | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20130208040509/http://www.joystiq.com/2013/02/06/ouya-partners-with-double-fine-and-words-with-friends-creator/ | archive-date = 2013-02-08 | url-status = dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.mcvuk.com/news/read/double-fine-adventure-exclusive-to-ouya-at-launch/0110537 | title = Double Fine Adventure exclusive to Ouya at launch | first = James | last = Batchelor | date = 2013-02-07 | accessdate = 2013-04-22 | publisher = [[MCV (magazine)|MCV]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20130211140700/http://www.mcvuk.com/news/read/double-fine-adventure-exclusive-to-ouya-at-launch/0110537# | archive-date = 2013-02-11 | url-status = dead }}</ref>\n\nAfter the Kickstarter, Double Fine launched a \"slacker backer\" program, which would allow players to pre-order the game through their site at a fixed cost, giving them access to the documentary and beta versions of the game once they were released.<ref name=\"polygon name\"/> The slacker backer option was also offered as part of the Double Fine [[Humble Bundle]] in May 2013 for those that purchased the bundle at a fixed price tier.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.polygon.com/2013/5/7/4305926/double-fine-humble-bundle-brutal-legend-psychonauts-mac-linux-pc | title = Double Fine Humble Bundle brings Brutal Legend, Costume Quest and more to Windows, Mac and Linux | publisher = [[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] | date = 2013-05-07 | accessdate = 2013-05-07 | first = Michael | last = McWhertor }}</ref>\n\n===Game development===\n''Broken Age'' began development under the codename \"Reds\", after Red's Place, following a Double Fine tradition of basing codenames on local [[Chinatown, San Francisco|Chinatown]] bars.<ref>{{cite episode |series=Double Fine Adventure! |number=3 |title=Codename: Reds |date=2012-06-27 |time=23:05 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=a_R2qKHdJlc&t=1385 |access-date=2015-12-26 |publisher=Double Fine Productions}}</ref> As Schafer had not written anything by the time development started, early efforts focused on creating a [[game engine]], art style, and answering technical questions. The [[open-source software|open-source]] [[Moai (software)|Moai game platform]] was chosen as the foundation for the game's engine. Nathan Martz, the technical director for Double Fine, stated that the open source nature of Moai allowed them to easily alter any aspect of the code base, while also supporting all of the targeted platforms.<ref name=\"lua\">{{cite web |url=http://gamasutra.com/view/news/169585/Double_Fines_Kickstarterfunded_adventure_game_to_use_the_Luabased_Moai_platform.php |title=Double Fine's Kickstarter-funded adventure game to use the Lua-based Moai platform |first=Tom |last=Curtis |date=2012-05-01 |access-date=2012-05-01 |publisher=[[Gamasutra]]}}</ref>\n\nProgrammers created a test game involving a red robot, while the artists created a mock-up test scenario to establish an art and animation style inspired by the fine art illustrations of lead artist Nathan Stapley, as well as to work out answers to basic interface questions. A sequence involving an unnamed lumberjack character and a cabin in the woods was created and the team decided to use a system of skeletal animation using segmented 2D characters. Once Schafer had established the basic storyline, involving the intersecting stories of a boy in a sci-fi world and a girl in a fantasy world, concept artists were gathered for an \"art jam\" to brainstorm and produce concept art for the game's creatures and locations. Schafer also asked the community for ideas, several of which were then illustrated by the concept artists.<ref>{{cite web |last=Schafer |first=Tim |title=Writing Update #3: Let's brainstorm Locations together! |url=http://www.doublefine.com/forums/viewthread/7054/ |work=Double Fine Action Forums |publisher=Double Fine Productions |access-date=1 June 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130808092237/http://www.doublefine.com/forums/viewthread/7054# |archive-date=2013-08-08 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nSchafer re-evaluated the state of the project in July 2013 and recognized that at their current rate, they would not be able to complete the game until 2015. For the first time in the company's history Double Fine decided to enlist the help of an outside studio, hiring SuperGenius to assist with art and animation.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://supergeniusstudio.com/project/broken-age/ |title=Broken Age |date=2014 |access-date=2015-12-26 |publisher=SuperGenius}}</ref> Double Fine also realized that they would run out of the Kickstarter funds before 2015, either requiring them to drastically cut back on the project or alter their release plans. Schafer opted to adjust the schedule and split the game into two acts, allowing them to fund the second act with money made from sales of the first.<ref>{{cite episode |series=Double Fine Adventure! |number=10 |title=Part One of Something Great |date=2013-07-02 |time=26:59 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RG5e6B5MHak&t=1619 |access-date=2016-01-01 |publisher=Double Fine Productions}}</ref> They had noticed that breaking the game into halves would fit naturally with events already occurring at the midpoint of the story, making the split relatively simple from a production perspective.<ref name=\"gi afterwords\">{{cite web |url=http://www.gameinformer.com/b/features/archive/2015/06/25/afterwords-broken-age.aspx |title=Afterwords \u2013 Broken Age In Retrospect With Tim Schafer |first=Ben |last=Hanson |date=2015-06-25 |access-date=2015-06-25 |work=[[Game Informer]]}}</ref>\n\nThe first playable version of the game was released on [[Steam (software)|Steam]]'s Early Access platform in January 2014, allowing Double Fine to obtain revenue from sales to fund the remaining development while gaining additional testing input before releasing a final version of the first act. Initial backlash to this announcement led Schafer to clarify that they were not asking for more money to develop the title, and that \"we are using our own money to deliver a bigger game than we Kickstarted\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.computerandvideogames.com/417616/double-fine-not-asking-for-more-money-stresses-schafer/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130706003512/http://www.computerandvideogames.com/417616/double-fine-not-asking-for-more-money-stresses-schafer/ |title=Double Fine 'not asking for more money,' stresses Schafer |first=Mike |last=Jackson |date=2013-07-03 |archive-date=2013-07-06 |access-date=2013-07-03 |work=[[Computer and Video Games]]}}</ref> In the end, the first act was deemed complete and polished enough to graduate from Early Access on January 28, with the second half to be released as a free update later in the year. By February 2014, Schafer confirmed that they had obtained enough from sales of Act 1 to complete the development and release of Act 2.<ref name=GISales>{{Cite web |url=http://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2014-02-21-tim-schafer-how-to-stay-afloat-in-a-pool-of-internet-twitter-hate |title=Schafer: How to stay afloat in \"a pool of Internet Twitter hate\" |first=Brendan |last=Sinclair |date=2014-02-21 |access-date=2014-02-21 |publisher=[[GamesIndustry.biz]]}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2014, producer Greg Rice announced that Schafer had finished writing the second act and the game's finale.<ref name=\"DFP 2014-10-23\">{{cite web |url=http://steamcommunity.com/app/232790/discussions/0/619569341079933147/ |title=Project Update-10/23/2014 |last=Rice |first=Greg |date=2014-10-23 |website=[[Steam (software)|Steam Community]] |publisher=[[Double Fine Productions]] |access-date=2014-11-13}}</ref> Though the second act was anticipated to be released in 2014, Schafer announced in November 2014 that they needed additional time to ensure the quality of Act 2 met expectations and pushed the release back to early 2015.<ref name=\"act2 delay 2015\">{{cite web |url=http://www.polygon.com/2014/11/30/7309373/broken-age-act-two-delayed |title=Broken Age's second act now aiming for early 2015 launch |first=Owne |last=Good |publisher=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] |date=2014-11-30 |access-date=2014-11-30}}</ref> Double Fine was able to use feedback from the first act's release to improve and alter some aspects of the second. One complaint of the first act was the simple nature of its puzzles, whose difficulty Double Fine increased for Act 2. The team also included a nod to a fan theory that had grown regarding the relation between Shay and Alex as a running joke in the second act.<ref name=\"gi afterwords\"/> The game's finale was planned out from the start, before the game was split into Acts; Schafer said he had taken influence of the end credits of ''[[My Neighbor Totoro]]'', which provides epilogue in the form of simple drawings alongside the running credits, to tell the fate of all the characters. He preferred this so that the narrative end of the game before the credits could be focused solely on Vella and Shay, instead of having each character appears to speak a line or so as to explain their fate.<ref name=\"gi afterwords\"/>\n\nA retail version of the game, containing both acts, for Windows, OS X, and Linux platforms will be published through partnership with [[Nordic Games GmbH|Nordic Games]], who had helped to bring retail releases of Double Fine's earlier games in 2014. The retail version will be released near the release of Act 2 for other platforms.<ref name=\"retail\"/> [[Limited Run Games]] will publish retail editions for the [[PlayStation 4]] and [[PlayStation Vita]] in June 2017.<ref>{{Cite web | url = http://kotaku.com/1795501738 | title = Broken Age - Limited Run Games | first = Mike | last = Fahey | date = May 23, 2017 | accessdate = May 24, 2017 | work = [[Kotaku]] }}</ref>\n\nSeveral voice actors who worked on previous Double Fine games voiced characters within ''Broken Age'', including [[Jennifer Hale]], [[Richard Horvitz]], [[Nick Jameson]], [[Nicki Rapp]], Ginny Westcott, and [[Jack Black]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gameinformer.com/games/broken_age/b/pc/archive/2013/09/01/jack-black-joins-the-vocal-cast-of-double-fine-39-s-broken-age.aspx |title=Jack Black Joins The Voice Cast Of Double Fine's Broken Age |first=Kyle |last=Hillard |date=2013-09-01 |access-date=2013-09-02 |work=[[Game Informer]]}}</ref> Other voice actors include [[Elijah Wood]], [[Pendleton Ward]], [[Wil Wheaton]], and [[Masasa Moyo]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gameinformer.com/b/news/archive/2013/11/03/adventure-time-creator-lending-his-voice-to-double-fine-39-s-broken-age.aspx |title=Adventure Time Creator Lending His Voice To Double Fine's Broken Age |first=Kyle |last=Hillard |date=2013-11-03 |access-date=2013-11-03 |work=[[Game Informer]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.polygon.com/2013/12/7/5186620/elijah-wood-broken-age-vgx-2013 |title=Elijah Wood joins the cast of Broken Age as Shay |first=Megan |last=Farokhmanesh |date=2013-12-07 |access-date=2013-12-07 |publisher=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]}}</ref> [[Alex Rigopulos]], the largest backer of the Kickstarter campaign, voiced a character that was designed in his likeness;<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gameinformer.com/games/broken_age/b/pc/archive/2013/12/05/wil-wheaton-leads-impressive-broken-age-voice-cast.aspx |title=Broken Age |first=Matt |last=Helgeson |date=2013-12-05 |access-date=2013-12-05 |work=[[Game Informer]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131209080108/http://www.gameinformer.com/games/broken_age/b/pc/archive/2013/12/05/wil-wheaton-leads-impressive-broken-age-voice-cast.aspx# |archive-date=2013-12-09 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Schafer decided to make the character effectively the same person Rigopulos was in both manner and appearance to minimize the amount of voice acting Rigopulos would need to do.<ref name=\"gi afterwords\"/> [[Days of Wonder]] was the second-largest backer, and through them, Double Fine included the character of the conductor from Days of Wonder's ''[[Ticket to Ride (board game)|Ticket to Ride]]'' games as part of one of Shay's mission rooms.<ref name=\"gi afterwords\"/>\n\n[[Peter McConnell]], who had worked with Schafer on many of his previous games, composed the music for ''Broken Age''. Initially McConnell planned to use only a small ensemble for the musical score but, as the game development progressed, he realized some parts needed a bigger orchestral sound.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://minnesota.publicradio.org/display/web/2014/02/13/peter-mcconnell-broken-age-on-top-score |title=Peter McConnell and Broken Age on Top Score |last=Reese |first=Emily |publisher=Minnesota Public Radio |date=2014-02-13 |access-date=2014-07-15}}</ref> The score was ultimately recorded by wind and string ensembles in San Francisco and the [[Melbourne Symphony Orchestra]], with McConnell overseeing the latter recording session with mixer [[Jory Prum]] remotely from [[Fairfax, California|Fairfax]], California.<ref name=\"polygon-mcconnell\">{{cite web |url=http://www.polygon.com/2014/1/17/5318754/broken-age-score-peter-mcconnell-release-date |title=Psychonauts, Grim Fandango composer wrote Broken Age score |last=Sarkar |first=Samit |publisher=Polygon |date=2014-01-17 |access-date=2014-07-15}}</ref> The score for the first act was released as a soundtrack album on the same day the first half of the game became publicly available.<ref name=\"polygon-mcconnell\"/> The soundtrack was released on vinyl in September 2016.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Cork|first1=James|title=Iam8bit Releasing Limited-Edition Psychonauts, Broken Age Vinyl At PAX|url=http://www.gameinformer.com/b/news/archive/2016/08/26/iam8bit-releasing-limited-edition-psychonauts-broken-age-vinyl-at-pax.aspx|accessdate=2016-09-09|work=Game Informer|date=2016-08-26}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[Electronic Entertainment Expo 2018]], Schafer announced that ''Broken Age'' will be available on the Switch later that year, alongside the remastered version of ''Grim Fandango''.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.usgamer.net/articles/double-fines-grim-fandango-and-broken-age-head-to-nintendo-switch | title = Double Fine's Grim Fandango and Broken Age Head to Nintendo Switch | first=  Jake | last = Green | date = June 13, 2018 | accessdate = June 13, 2018 | work = [[USGamer]] }}</ref>\n\n===Documentary===\nThe development process of ''Broken Age'' was recorded by 2 Player Productions as part of the Kickstarter project. In 2011, Paul Owens of 2 Player Productions wrote an e-mail to Greg Rice and Tim Schafer of Double Fine Productions with a proposition of making a documentary series charting the development of a game from beginning to end. A part of the Kickstarter money was set aside for the documentary.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Dineen|first1=Declan|title=Double Fine Adventure is the best video game documentary to date|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2015-07-29-double-fine-adventure-is-the-greatest-video-game-documentary-to-date|website=[[Eurogamer]]|publisher=Gamer Network|accessdate=2015-07-31|date=2015-07-30}}</ref> The documentary was originally only available to backers, but as of March 2015, the company has started providing the episodes free of charge to YouTube.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.vg247.com/2015/03/04/double-fine-adventure-kickstarter-documentary-releasing-free-on-youtube/ | title = Double Fine Adventure Kickstarter documentary releasing free on YouTube | first = Brenna | last = Hillier | date = 2015-03-03 | accessdate = 2015-03-03 | publisher = [[VG247]] }}</ref> The documentary has received praise for being an honest, open look into the game's development process.<ref>http://au.ign.com/articles/2015/03/27/this-incredible-broken-age-documentary-is-now-free</ref><ref>https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2015/07/20/the-final-episode-of-double-fine-adventure-is-out/#more-302713</ref><ref>http://kotaku.com/if-you-care-about-how-video-games-are-made-watch-the-d-1759216480</ref><ref>https://www.destructoid.com/the-wonderful-double-fine-adventure-documentary-is-going-free-288530.phtml</ref><ref>https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2015/03/double-fine-adventure-documentary-shows-the-woes-o.html</ref><ref>https://arstechnica.com/gaming/2015/10/broken-ages-making-of-documentary-may-be-double-fines-most-enduring-legacy/</ref><ref>http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2015-07-29-double-fine-adventure-is-the-greatest-video-game-documentary-to-date</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n{{Video game reviews\n| title = \n| MC = PC: 76/100<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/broken-age |title=Broken Age for PC Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=2018-07-26}}</ref><br />(Act 1) PC: 82/100<ref name=\"MCPCA1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/broken-age-act-1 |title=Broken Age: Act 1 for PC Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=2018-07-26}}</ref><br />(Act 1) iOS: 76/100<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/ios/broken-age-act-1 |title=Broken Age: Act 1 for iPhone/iPad Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=2018-07-26}}</ref><br />(Act 2) PC: 73/100<ref name=\"MCPCA2\">{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/broken-age-act-2 |title=Broken Age: Act 2 for PC Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=2018-07-26}}</ref><br />PS4: 81/100<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/playstation-4/broken-age |title=Broken Age for PlayStation 4 Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=2018-07-26}}</ref><br />VITA: 90/100<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/playstation-vita/broken-age |title=Broken Age for PlayStation Vita Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=2018-07-26}}</ref><br />XONE: 78/100<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/xbox-one/broken-age |title=Broken Age for Xbox One Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=2018-07-26}}</ref>\n| Destruct = 9.5/10<ref name=DtoidRev1>{{Cite web | url = http://www.destructoid.com/review-broken-age-act-1-269349.phtml | title = Broken Age Act 1 | publisher = [[Destructoid]] | accessdate = 2014-02-01 }}</ref>\n| EuroG = 7/10<ref name=EuroRev1>{{cite web | url = http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2014-01-16-broken-age-act-1-review | title = Broken Age Act 1 review | first = Dan | last = Whitehead | date= 2014-01-16 | accessdate = 2014-01-16 | publisher = [[Eurogamer]]}}</ref>\n| GI = 8/10<ref name=GIRev1>{{cite web | url = http://www.gameinformer.com/games/broken_age/b/pc/archive/2014/01/14/broken-age-act-i-review.aspx | title = Broken Age Act 1 review | first = Jeff | last = Cork | date = 2014-01-14 | accessdate = 2014-01-16 | work = [[Game Informer]] }}</ref>\n| GSpot = 7/10<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.gamespot.com/reviews/broken-age-act-i-review/1900-6415631/ |title=Broken Age Act I Review| first = Maxwell | last = McGee | date = 2014-01-15 | accessdate = 2014-12-07 | work = [[GameSpot]]}}</ref>\n| IGN = 9.5/10<ref name=IGNRev1>{{cite web | url = http://www.ign.com/articles/2014/01/16/broken-age-act-i-review | title = Broken Age, Act 1 | first = Marty | last = Sliva | date = 2014-01-16 | accessdate = 2014-01-16 | publisher = [[IGN]] }}</ref>\n| Poly = 9/10<ref name=PolyRev1>{{cite web | url = http://www.polygon.com/2014/1/15/5309804/broken-age-review | title = Broken Age Act 1 | first = Justin | last= McElroy | date = 2014-01-15 | accessdate = 2014-01-16 | publisher = [[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] }}</ref>\n| rev1 = ''[[TouchArcade]]''\n| rev1Score = iOS: {{rating|3|5}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://toucharcade.com/2014/06/17/broken-age-part-1-review/ |title='Broken Age' Part 1 Review \u2013 An Uneven Split |last=Dotson |first=Carter |date=2014-06-17 |website=[[TouchArcade]] |accessdate=2018-07-26}}</ref>\n}}\n\nThe game's first act was well received by critics, scoring 82/100 on [[review aggregation]] website [[Metacritic]].<ref name=\"MCPCA1\" /> [[Adam Sessler]] of [[Rev3games|Rev3Games]] gave ''Broken Age'' Act 1 a 4/5 calling it a beautiful game with wonderful and funny writing.<ref>{{cite web|last=Sessler|first=Adam|title=Broken Age (Part 1) REVIEW! Adam Sessler Reviews|url=http://revision3.com/rev3gamesreviews/broken-age-1-review|work=Rev3Games|publisher=Revision3|accessdate=28 February 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140203125922/http://revision3.com/rev3gamesreviews/broken-age-1-review#|archive-date=2014-02-03|url-status=dead}}</ref> [[Justin McElroy]], writing at [[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] highlighted the game's characters as \"grounded while approaching absurdity and adversity with brave, heartfelt sincerity\" giving the game a \"kind of depth that's so often lacking in other 'funny' games\".<ref name=PolyRev1/> Within a month of the first act's release, Schafer confirmed that its sales would be sufficient to cover the remaining development costs for Act 2.<ref name=GISales/>\n\nAct 2, released more than a year later, received a similar response overall, with a Metacritic score of 73/100.<ref name=\"MCPCA2\"/> Despite this, many critics saw the second act as a letdown following the success of the first: John Walker of [[Rock Paper Shotgun]] praised the art and voice acting, but criticised Act 2 for its re-use of locations from Act 1 and lackluster ending,<ref name=\"RPSAct2review\">{{Cite web | url = https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2015/04/27/broken-age-act-2-review/#more-281815 | accessdate = 2016-07-19 | title = Wot I Think: Broken Age Act 2 | publisher = [[Rock Paper Shotgun]] | author = John Walker}}</ref> following up his review with a lengthy article expanding on his criticism of the story.<ref name=\"RPSAct2article\">{{Cite web | url = https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2015/04/29/broken-age-plot/ | title = Why Broken Age Act 2's Story Is An Awful Mess | accessdate=2016-07-19 | publisher=[[Rock Paper Shotgun]] | author = John Walker}}</ref> Other critics had similar complaints,<ref name=\"DSAct2review\">{{Cite web | url = http://www.digitalspy.com/gaming/review/a644942/broken-age-act-2-review-a-surprisingly-mishandled-finale/ | title = Broken Age Act 2 review: A surprisingly mishandled finale | author = Scott Nichols | publisher = [[Digital Spy]] | accessdate = 2016-07-19 }}</ref><ref name = PCWorldAct2review>{{Cite web | url = http://www.pcworld.com/article/2921481/broken-age-act-two-review-wasted-potential.html | title = Broken Age (Act Two) review: Wasted potential | accessdate = 2016-07-19 | publisher = [[PC World]] | author = Hayden Dingman }}</ref> including Justin McElroy, who in an update to his initial Act 1 review, was disappointed by too much puzzling in the second half.<ref name=PolyRev1/> He also echoed a common criticism of the frustrating difficulty of the puzzles, which many reviewers felt were much harder than in Act 1, especially if players tried to pick it up without replaying the first half.<ref name=\"RPSAct2review\" /><ref name = DSAct2review /><ref name=\"KotakuAct2review\">{{Cite web | url = http://kotaku.com/the-final-part-of-broken-age-is-a-bittersweet-ending-to-1700440814 | accessdate=2016-07-19 | title = The Final Part of Broken Age Is a Bittersweet Ending to a Great Game | author = Evan Narcisse | publisher = [[Kotaku]] }}</ref>\n\n===Impact===\n{{see also|Crowdfunding in video games}}\nThe success of the fund-raising campaign established crowd-sourcing as a challenge to publisher funding (and control) for multimillion-dollar projects. [[John Walker (journalist)|John Walker]] from [[Rock, Paper, Shotgun]] was quick to point out that this doesn't pose a major threat to publishers on a large scale, but added that it would force publishers to ask themselves questions such as \"Are we really in touch with our audience\u2019s desires?\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2012/02/09/thought-double-fines-kickstarter-asks-some-big-questions/ |title=Thought: Double Fine's Kickstarter Asks Big Questions |publisher=Rock, Paper, Shotgun | first = John | last = Walker|date=2012-02-09 |accessdate=2012-02-10}}</ref> Johnny Cullen of [[VG247]] compared the Double Fine Kickstarter to the release of [[Radiohead]]'s album ''[[In Rainbows]]'', which the band had sold through their website in a [[pay-what-you-want]] model prior to a physical printing, without the interference of a music publisher. Cullen noted the model of crowd-sourcing has previously not worked for some game developers, and does not expect it to be a guaranteed success for future efforts, as he believes Double Fine is a unique studio with a dedicated fan base, aspects that are not shared by all developers.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.vg247.com/2012/02/09/double-fines-kickstart-provides-a-radiohead-moment/ | title = Double Fine's Kickstarter provides a Radiohead moment | publisher = [[VG247]] | first = Johnny | last = Cullen | date = 2012-02-09 | accessdate = 2012-02-09 }}</ref>\n\nInitial commentary largely framed Double Fine as exceptional, citing Double Fine's reputation,<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.edge-online.com/features/devs-celebrate-double-fines-kickstarter-success | title = Devs celebrate Double Fine's Kickstarter success | date = 2012-02-10 | accessdate = 2012-02-10 | work = [[Edge (magazine)|Edge]] }}</ref> experience with the under-serviced genre,<ref>{{cite web | url = http://kotaku.com/5883864/why-the-internet-gave-this-video-game-1-million-in-a-single-day | title = Why the Internet Gave This Man $1 Million. In a Single Day. | first = Luke | last = Plunkett | date = 2012-02-09 | accessdate = 2012-02-10 | publisher = Kotaku }}</ref> and history of difficulty with publisher funding<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2012-02-15-the-kickstarter-conundrum | title= The Kickstarter Conundrum |  date = 2012-02-15 | accessdate  = 2012-02-15 | publisher = [[Eurogamer]] | first = Dan | last = Whitehead }}</ref> as reasons why Double Fine's case was unique. Initially, many remained skeptical that such a level of success could be replicated.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.giantbomb.com/news/on-kickstarter-there-are-no-guarantees/4055/ | title = On Kickstarter, There Are No Guarantees | first = Patrick | last = Klepek | date = 2012-03-27 | accessdate = 2012-03-28 | publisher = [[Giant Bomb]] }}</ref> Schafer further agreed that the success of the Double Fine Kickstarter would be somewhat difficult to replicate for other games, even for Double Fine, as it would require the project to be \"a good story for people to get behind\".<ref name=\"gb interview\"/>\n\nInitial fears that this success would be isolated were allayed as new projects emerged. As the ''Double Fine Adventure'' campaign closed, [[Brian Fargo]] of [[inXile Entertainment]] launched a Kickstarter to fund development of the sequel ''[[Wasteland 2]]'', which met its target of $900,000 in funding within two days,<ref name=\"Curtis\">{{cite web | url = http://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/40362/Wasteland_creator_looks_to_Kickstarter_for_series_revival.php | title = Wasteland creator looks to Kickstarter for series revival  | first = Tom | last = Curtis | date = 2012-02-16 | accessdate = 2012-02-16 | publisher = [[Gamasutra]] }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.vg247.com/2012/03/14/wasteland-2-kickstarter-raises-over-500k-on-day-one/ | title =  Kickstarter: Schafer closes on $3.3m, Wasteland 2 raises over $500k in one day | first = Dave | last = Oshry | date = 2012-03-14 | accessdate = 2012-03-14 | publisher = [[VG247]] }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/165868/Wasteland_2_Kickstarter_surpasses_900K_goal_in_2_days.php | title = Wasteland 2 Kickstarter surpasses $900K goal in 2 days | first = Mike | last = Rose | date = 2012-03-15 | accessdate = 2012-03-15 | publisher = [[Gamasutra]] }}</ref> and eventually raised more than $2.9 million. ''Double Fine Adventure'' brought in 61,692 new users to Kickstarter, and greatly increased the platform's visibility and viability for funding of games projects.<ref>[http://www.kickstarter.com/blog/blockbuster-effects Blockbuster Effects \u00bb The Kickstarter Blog \u2014 Kickstarter]. Kickstarter.com (2012-03-29). Retrieved on 2014-01-14.</ref> Within the six weeks following the launch of the Double Fine Adventure Kickstarter, the site raised more than $2.9 million in pledges (outside of the Double Fine project) for video game related projects, compared with $1.7 million total for the category in the prior two years, as well as increasing the amount of funding coming into projects of all categories.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/167549/Double_Fine_Kickstarter_brings_huge_boost_to_crowdfunded_games.php | title = \tDouble Fine Kickstarter brings huge boost to crowd-funded games  | first = Tom | last = Curtis | date = 2012-03-29 | accessdate = 2012-03-29 | publisher = [[Gamasutra]] }}</ref> In October, ''[[Project Eternity]]'' surpassed Double Fine's funding record, further suggesting the crowd-funding model will continue to be a part of the gaming landscape.<ref>[http://www.nbcnews.com/technology/ingame/project-eternity-raises-3-9-million-sets-kickstarter-record-1C6522242 'Project Eternity' raises $3.9 million, sets Kickstarter record]. NBC News.com (2012-10-17). Retrieved on 2014-01-14.</ref>\n\nThe success of ''Double Fine Adventure'' has had a particularly visible impact on the adventure genre, inspiring several other established adventure game developers to use Kickstarter as a means to return to the genre.<ref name=\"1UP\">{{cite web |url=http://www.1up.com/features/adventure-game-kickstarter-roundup |title=Your Adventure Game Kickstarter Roundup |last=Mackey |first=Bob |date=12 June 2012 |accessdate=28 August 2013 |publisher=[[1UP.com]] }}</ref> In the months following its release, the creators of ''[[Broken Sword]]'',<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kickstarter.com/projects/revolutionsoftware/broken-sword-the-serpents-curse-adventure |title=Broken Sword - the Serpent's Curse Adventure by Revolution Software \u2014 Kickstarter |publisher=Kickstarter |accessdate= }}</ref> ''[[Gabriel Knight]]'',<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kickstarter.com/projects/1005365109/jane-jensens-pinkerton-road-2012-2013-csg |title=Jane Jensen's Moebius and Pinkerton Road Studio by Jane Jensen \u2014 Kickstarter |publisher=Kickstarter |accessdate= }}</ref> ''[[Leisure Suit Larry]]'',<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kickstarter.com/projects/leisuresuitlarry/make-leisure-suit-larry-come-again |title=Make Leisure Suit Larry come again! by Replay Games \u2014 Kickstarter |publisher=Kickstarter |accessdate= }}</ref> ''[[Space Quest]]''<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kickstarter.com/projects/spaceventure/two-guys-spaceventure-by-the-creators-of-space-que |title=Two Guys SpaceVenture - by the creators of Space Quest by Two Guys From Andromeda \u2014 Kickstarter |publisher=Kickstarter |accessdate= }}</ref> and ''[[Tex Murphy]]''<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kickstarter.com/projects/texmurphy/tex-murphy-project-fedora |title=Tex Murphy - Project Fedora by Chris Jones & Aaron Conners \u2014 Kickstarter |publisher=Kickstarter |accessdate= }}</ref> have all managed to raise amounts in excess of Schafer's original goal of $400,000.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|http://www.brokenagegame.com/}}\n\n{{Tim Schafer}}\n{{Double Fine Productions}}\n{{Portal bar|Video games}}\n\n[[Category:2014 video games]]\n[[Category:2015 video games]]\n[[Category:Android (operating system) games]]\n[[Category:Coming-of-age fiction]]\n[[Category:Double Fine Productions]]\n[[Category:Episodic video games]]\n[[Category:IOS games]]\n[[Category:Kickstarter-funded video games]]\n[[Category:Linux games]]\n[[Category:Lua-scripted video games]]\n[[Category:MacOS games]]\n[[Category:Nintendo Switch games]]\n[[Category:Ouya games]]\n[[Category:PlayStation 4 games]]\n[[Category:PlayStation Network games]]\n[[Category:PlayStation Vita games]]\n[[Category:Point-and-click adventure games]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in the United States]]\n[[Category:Video games scored by Peter McConnell]]\n[[Category:Video games featuring female protagonists]]\n[[Category:Windows games]]\n[[Category:Xbox One games]]\n", "name_user": "AntiGravityMaster", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Broken_Age"}
{"title_page": "Chick Evans (coach)", "text_new": "{{For|the 1910s and 1920s amateur golfer|Chick Evans}}\n{{Infobox college coach\n| name = Chick Evans\n| image = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date|1901|6|18}}\n| birth_place = [[Illinois]]\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|1976|11|23|1901|7|18}}\n| death_place = [[San Diego|San Diego, California]]\n| alma_mater = [[Des Moines University (1865\u20131929)|Des Moines University]] (1923)<ref name=\"google\">{{cite book|title=The Blue Book of College Athletics|date=1948|publisher=F. Turbyville|issn=0893-7737|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xHxYAAAAYAAJ|accessdate=December 2, 2014}}</ref>\n| player_sport1 = Football\n| player_years2 = 1918\n| player_team2 = [[Illinois Fighting Illini football|Illinois]]\n| player_years3 = c. 1920\n| player_team3 = [[Des Moines Tigers football|Des Moines]]\n| player_positions = \n| coach_sport1 = Football\n| coach_years2 = 1924\u20131927\n| coach_team2 = [[Boone High School|Boone HS (IA)]]\n| coach_years3 = 1928\n| coach_team3 = [[DeKalb High School (Illinois)|DeKalb HS (IL)]]\n| coach_years4 = 1929\u20131954\n| coach_team4 = [[Northern Illinois Huskies football|Northern Illinois State]]\n| coach_sport5 = Basketball\n| coach_years6 = 1924\u20131927\n| coach_team6 = [[Boone High School|Boone HS (IA)]]\n| coach_years7 = 1928\u20131929\n| coach_team7 = [[DeKalb High School (Illinois)|DeKalb HS (IL)]]\n| coach_years8 = 1929\u20131940\n| coach_team8 = [[Northern Illinois Huskies men's basketball|Northern Illinois State]]\n| coach_sport9 = Baseball\n| coach_years10 = 1930\u20131934\n| coach_team10 = [[Northern Illinois Huskies baseball|Northern Illinois State]]\n| coach_years11 = 1937\u20131944\n| coach_team11 = [[Northern Illinois Huskies baseball|Northern Illinois State]]\n| coach_years12 = 1946\u20131947\n| coach_team12 = [[Northern Illinois Huskies baseball|Northern Illinois State]]\n| admin_years1 = 1929\u20131968\n| admin_team1 = [[Northern Illinois Huskies|Northern Illinois State / Northern Illinois]]\n| overall_record = 132\u201370\u201320 (college football)<br>125\u201393 (college basketball)<br>118\u2013115\u20133 (college baseball)\n| bowl_record = 0\u20132\n| tournament_record = \n| championships = Football<br>5 [[Illinois Intercollegiate Athletic Conference|IIAC]] (1938, 1941, 1944, 1946, 1951)\n| awards = \n| coaching_records = \n}}\n'''George G. \"Chick\" Evans''' (June 18, 1901 \u2013 November 23, 1976) was an [[American football]], [[basketball]], and [[baseball]] coach and college athletics administrator. He served as the head football coach at [[Northern Illinois University]] from 1929 to 1954, compiling a record of 132\u201370\u201320. Evans was also the head basketball coach at Northern Illinois from 1929 to 1940, tallying a mark of 125\u201393, and served three stints at head baseball coach at the school (1930\u20131934, 1937\u20131944, 1946\u20131947), amassing a record of 118\u2013115\u20133. Evans was the [[athletic director]] at Northern Illinois from 1929 to 1968. His 132 wins are the most of any head coach in the [[Northern Illinois Huskies football]] program's history.\n\nA native of [[El Paso, Illinois]], Evans attended the [[University of Illinois at Urbana\u2013Champaign|University of Illinois]], where was a member of the [[1918 Illinois Fighting Illini football team]] led by head coach [[Robert Zuppke]]. He then moved on to the now-defunct [[Des Moines University (1865\u20131929)|Des Moines University]] in [[Des Moines, Iowa]], which was later acquired by the [[University of Sioux Falls]]; this should not be confused with the present [[Des Moines University]]. At Des Moines, Evans won 11 varsity letters and captained teams in four different sports directed by head coach [[Harry M. Bell]].\n\nEvans began his coaching career at [[Boone High School]] in [[Boone, Iowa]], where he spent four years before moving to [[DeKalb High School (Illinois)|DeKalb High School]] in [[DeKalb, Illinois]] for one year.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Evans Signed as Coach by State Teachers' College |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/42904066/the_daily_chronicle/ |newspaper=[[Daily Chronicle (Illinois)|Daily Chronicle]] |location=[[DeKalb, Illinois]] |date=May 23, 1929 |page=1 |access-date=January 24, 2020 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] {{Open access}} }}</ref>\n\nEvans later earned a master's degree from [[Columbia University]]. He died on November 23, 1976, at Kearney-Mesa Convalesclent Hospital in [[San Diego|San Diego, California]] after a short illness.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title='Chick' Evans dies at 76 |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/42903904/obituary_for_chick_evans_aged_76/ |newspaper=[[Daily Chronicle (Illinois)|Daily Chronicle]] |location=[[DeKalb, Illinois]] |date=November 24, 1976 |page=1 |access-date=January 24, 2020 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] {{Open access}} }}</ref> Evans and his wife, Venus, had moved there following his retirement as athletic director at Northern Illinois in 1968.<ref>''Daily Messenger'', November 24, 1976, Canandaigua, New York</ref>\n\n==Head coaching record==\n===College football===\n{{CFB Yearly Record Start | type = coach | team = | conf = | bowl = | poll = no }}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Subhead\n | name      = [[Northern Illinois Huskies football|Northern Illinois State Teachers/Evansmen/Huskies]]\n | conf      = [[Interstate Intercollegiate Athletic Conference|Illinois/Interstate Intercollegiate Athletic Conference]]\n | startyear = 1929\n | endyear   = 1954\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Entry\n | championship = \n | year         = [[1929 college football season|1929]]\n | name         = [[1929 Northern Illinois State Teachers football team|Northern Illinois State]]\n | overall      = 6\u20131\u20131\n | conference   = 3\u20131\u20131\n | confstanding = \n | bowlname     = \n | bowloutcome  = \n | bcsbowl      = \n | ranking      = no\n | ranking2     = no\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly 