inois State\n | overall    = 132\u201370\u201320\n | confrecord = 73\u201342\u201312\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record End\n | overall  = 132\u201370\u201320\n | bowls    = no\n | poll     = no\n | polltype = \n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{navboxes|list=\n{{Northern Illinois Huskies athletic director navbox}}\n{{Northern Illinois Huskies football coach navbox}}\n{{Northern Illinois Huskies men's basketball coach navbox}}\n{{Northern Illinois Huskies baseball coach navbox}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Evans, Chick}}\n[[Category:1901 births]]\n[[Category:1976 deaths]]\n[[Category:Des Moines Tigers football players]]\n[[Category:Illinois Fighting Illini football players]]\n[[Category:Northern Illinois Huskies athletic directors]]\n[[Category:Northern Illinois Huskies baseball coaches]]\n[[Category:Northern Illinois Huskies football coaches]]\n[[Category:Northern Illinois Huskies men's basketball coaches]]\n[[Category:High school basketball coaches in Illinois]]\n[[Category:High school basketball coaches in Iowa]]\n[[Category:High school football coaches in Illinois]]\n[[Category:High school football coaches in Iowa]]\n[[Category:Columbia University alumni]]\n[[Category:People from El Paso, Illinois]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Illinois]]\n\n{{1920s-collegefootball-coach-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{For|the 1910s and 1920s amateur golfer|Chick Evans}}\n{{Infobox college coach\n| name = Chick Evans\n| image = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date|1901|6|18}}\n| birth_place = [[Illinois]]\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|1976|11|23|1901|7|18}}\n| death_place = [[San Diego|San Diego, California]]\n| alma_mater = [[Des Moines University (1865\u20131929)|Des Moines University]] (1923)<ref name=\"google\">{{cite book|title=The Blue Book of College Athletics|date=1948|publisher=F. Turbyville|issn=0893-7737|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xHxYAAAAYAAJ|accessdate=December 2, 2014}}</ref>\n| player_sport1 = Football\n| player_years2 = 1918\n| player_team2 = [[Illinois Fighting Illini football|Illinois]]\n| player_years3 = c. 1920\n| player_team3 = [[Des Moines Tigers football|Des Moines]]\n| player_positions = \n| coach_sport1 = Football\n| coach_years2 = 1924\u20131927\n| coach_team2 = [[Boone High School|Boone HS (IA)]]\n| coach_years3 = 1928\n| coach_team3 = [[DeKalb High School (Illinois)|DeKalb HS (IL)]]\n| coach_years4 = 1929\u20131954\n| coach_team4 = [[Northern Illinois Huskies football|Northern Illinois State]]\n| coach_sport5 = Basketball\n| coach_years6 = 1924\u20131927\n| coach_team6 = [[Boone High School|Boone HS (IA)]]\n| coach_years7 = 1928\u20131929\n| coach_team7 = [[DeKalb High School (Illinois)|DeKalb HS (IL)]]\n| coach_years8 = 1929\u20131940\n| coach_team8 = [[Northern Illinois Huskies men's basketball|Northern Illinois State]]\n| coach_sport9 = Baseball\n| coach_years10 = 1930\u20131934\n| coach_team10 = [[Northern Illinois Huskies baseball|Northern Illinois State]]\n| coach_years11 = 1937\u20131944\n| coach_team11 = [[Northern Illinois Huskies baseball|Northern Illinois State]]\n| coach_years12 = 1946\u20131947\n| coach_team12 = [[Northern Illinois Huskies baseball|Northern Illinois State]]\n| admin_years1 = 1929\u20131968\n| admin_team1 = [[Northern Illinois Huskies|Northern Illinois State / Northern Illinois]]\n| overall_record = 132\u201370\u201320 (college football)<br>125\u201393 (college basketball)<br>118\u2013115\u20133 (college baseball)\n| bowl_record = 0\u20132\n| tournament_record = \n| championships = Football<br>5 [[Illinois Intercollegiate Athletic Conference|IIAC]] (1938, 1941, 1944, 1946, 1951)\n| awards = \n| coaching_records = \n}}\n'''George G. \"Chick\" Evans''' (June 18, 1901 \u2013 November 23, 1976) was an [[American football]], [[basketball]], and [[baseball]] coach and college athletics administrator. He served as the head football coach at [[Northern Illinois University]] from 1929 to 1954, compiling a record of 132\u201370\u201320. Evans was also the head basketball coach at Northern Illinois from 1929 to 1940, tallying a mark of 125\u201393, and served three stints at head baseball coach at the school (1930\u20131934, 1937\u20131944, 1946\u20131947), amassing a record of 118\u2013115\u20133. Evans was the [[athletic director]] at Northern Illinois from 1929 to 1968. His 132 wins are the most of any head coach in the [[Northern Illinois Huskies football]] program's history.\n\nA native of [[El Paso, Illinois]], Evans attended the [[University of Illinois at Urbana\u2013Champaign|University of Illinois]], where was a member of the [[1918 Illinois Fighting Illini football team]] led by head coach [[Robert Zuppke]]. He then moved on to the now-defunct [[Des Moines University (1865\u20131929)|Des Moines University]] in [[Des Moines, Iowa]], which was later acquired by the [[University of Sioux Falls]]; this should not be confused with the present [[Des Moines University]]. At Des Moines, Evans won 11 varsity letters and captained teams in four different sports directed by head coach [[Harry M. Bell]].\n\nEvans began his coaching career at [[Boone High School]] in [[Boone, Iowa]], where he spent four years before moving to [[DeKalb High School (Illinois)|DeKalb High School]] in [[DeKalb, Illinois]] for one year.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Evans Signed as Coach by State Teachers' College |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/42904066/the_daily_chronicle/ |newspaper=[[Daily Chronicle (Illinois)|Daily Chronicle]] |location=[[DeKalb, Illinois]] |date=May 23, 1929 |page=1 |access-date=January 24, 2020 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] {{Open access}} }}</ref>\n\nEvans later earned a master's degree from [[Columbia University]]. He died on November 23, 1976, at Kearney-Mesa Convensclent Hispital in [[San Diego|San Diego, California]] after a short illness.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title='Chick' Evans dies at 76 |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/42903904/obituary_for_chick_evans_aged_76/ |newspaper=[[Daily Chronicle (Illinois)|Daily Chronicle]] |location=[[DeKalb, Illinois]] |date=November 24, 1976 |page=1 |access-date=January 24, 2020 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] {{Open access}} }}</ref> Evans and his wife, Venus, had moved there following his retirement as athletic director at Northern Illinois in 1968.<ref>''Daily Messenger'', November 24, 1976, Canandaigua, New York</ref>\n\n==Head coaching record==\n===College football===\n{{CFB Yearly Record Start | type = coach | team = | conf = | bowl = | poll = no }}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Subhead\n | name      = [[Northern Illinois Huskies football|Northern Illinois State Teachers/Evansmen/Huskies]]\n | conf      = [[Interstate Intercollegiate Athletic Conference|Illinois/Interstate Intercollegiate Athletic Conference]]\n | startyear = 1929\n | endyear   = 1954\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Entry\n | championship = \n | year         = [[1929 college football season|1929]]\n | name         = [[1929 Northern Illinois State Teachers football team|Northern Illinois State]]\n | overall      = 6\u20131\u20131\n | conference   = 3\u20131\u20131\n | confstanding = \n | bowlname     = \n | bowloutcome  = \n | bcsbowl      = \n | ranking      = no\n | ranking2     = no\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Entry\n | championship = \n | year         = [[1930 college football season|1930]]\n | name         = [[1930 Northern Illinois State Evansmen football team|Northern Illinois State]]\n | overall      = 6\u20132\u20131\n | conference   = 3\u20131\u20131\n | confstanding = \n | bowlname     = \n | bowloutcome  = \n | bcsbowl      = \n | ranking      = no\n | ranking2     = no\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Entry\n | championship = \n | year         = [[1931 college football season|1931]]\n | name         = [[1931 Northern Illinois State Evansmen football team|Northern Illinois State]]\n | overall      = 5\u20133\n | conference   = 4\u20132\n | confstanding = \n | bowlname     = \n | bowloutcome  = \n | bcsbowl      = \n