 City: People, Place, and the Meaning of Modern Austin'' (University of Texas Press; 2010) 273 pages; traces the history of environmentalism in the Texas capital, which has been part of a larger effort to preserve Austin's quality of life and sense of place.\n\n== External links ==\n{{Sister project links\n|voy = Austin, Texas\n}}\n* [http://www.austintexas.gov/ AustinTexas.gov] - official city website\n* [http://www.austintexas.org/ Austin Convention & Visitors Bureau]\n* [http://www.austinchamber.com/ Austin Chamber of Commerce]\n* [http://texashistory.unt.edu/browse/contributor/ASPL/ Historic photographs from the Austin History Center], hosted by the [http://texashistory.unt.edu/ Portal to Texas History]\n* {{Handbook of Texas |id = hda03 |name = Austin}}\n* {{osmrelation|113314}}\n\n{{-}}\n{{Austin}}\n{{Greater Austin}}\n{{Republic of Texas}}\n{{Texas}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title = Other articles related to Austin\n|list =\n{{Travis County, Texas}}\n{{Hays County, Texas}}\n{{Williamson County, Texas}}\n{{US state capitals}}\n{{Texas county seats}}\n{{Texas cities and mayors of 100,000 population}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Austin, Texas| ]]<!--please leave the empty space as standard-->\n[[Category:Cities in Texas]]\n[[Category:Cities in Hays County, Texas]]\n[[Category:Cities in Travis County, Texas]]\n[[Category:Cities in Williamson County, Texas]]\n[[Category:University towns in the United States]]\n[[Category:County seats in Texas]]\n[[Category:Cities in Greater Austin]]\n[[Category:Planned cities in the United States]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1839]]\n[[Category:1839 establishments in the Republic of Texas]]\n[[Category:Academic enclaves]]\n[[Category:Capitals of former nations]]\n", "name_user": "Biscuitsandcrazy", "label": "safe", "comment": "Removed LGBT community from a list of professions", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Austin,_Texas"}
{"title_page": "Binary form", "text_new": "{{About|the musical form}}\n[[Image:Binary form.png|thumb|400px|Binary form in major and minor keys. Each section must be at least three phrases long.<ref>White, John D. (1976). ''The Analysis of Music'', p.50. {{ISBN|0-13-033233-X}}.</ref>]]\n\n'''Binary form''' is a [[musical form]] in 2 related sections, both of which are usually repeated. Binary is also a structure used to choreograph [[dance]]. In music this is usually performed as A-A-B-B.\n\nBinary form was popular during the [[Baroque music|Baroque period]], often used to structure movements of [[keyboard instrument|keyboard]] [[sonata (music)|sonatas]]. It was also used for short, one-movement works.  Around the middle of the 18th century, the form largely fell from use as the principal design of entire movements as [[sonata form]] and organic [[musical development|development]] gained prominence. When it is found in later works, it usually takes the form of the theme in a set of [[variation form|variation]]s, or the [[Minuet]], [[Scherzo]], or Trio sections of a \"minuet and trio\" or \"scherzo and trio\" movement in a [[sonata]], [[symphony]], etc. Many larger forms incorporate binary structures, and many more complicated forms (such as the 18th-century [[sonata form]]) share certain characteristics with binary form.\n\n==Structure==\nMost strictly, a piece in binary form is characterized by two complementary, related sections of roughly equal duration, which come up frequently. The first section will start in a certain [[key (music)|key]], and will usually [[Modulation (music)|modulate]] to a [[closely related key|related key]]:\n*compositions in major keys will typically modulate to the [[dominant (music)|dominant]], the fifth scale degree above the [[tonic (music)|tonic]]\n*compositions in minor keys will typically modulate to the [[relative key|relative major]], the major key centered on the third scale degree above the tonic; alternatively the first section could close in the dominant minor, or with an imperfect [[cadence (music)|cadence]] in the original key.\n\nThe second section of the piece begins in the newly established key, where it remains for an indefinite period of time. After some  harmonic activity, the piece will eventually modulate back to its original key before ending. More often than not, especially in 18th-century compositions, the A and B sections are separated by [[bar (music)|double bars]] with repeat signs, meaning both sections were to be repeated.<ref>Bartlette, Christopher, and Steven G. Laitz (2010).  Graduate Review of Tonal Theory.  New York: Oxford University Press, pg 156.  {{ISBN|978-0-19-537698-2}}</ref>\n\nBinary form is usually characterised as having the form ''AB'', though since both sections repeat, a more accurate description would be ''AABB''.  Others, however, prefer to use the label ''AA\u2032''.  This second designation points to the fact that there is no great change in character between the two sections. The [[rhythm]]s and [[melody|melodic]] material used will generally be closely related in each section, and if the piece is written for a [[musical ensemble]], the [[Instrumentation (music)|instrumentation]] will generally be the same. This is in contrast to the use of [[verse-chorus form]] in [[popular music]]\u2014the contrast between the two sections is primarily one of the keys used.\n\n==Further distinctions==\nA piece in binary form can be further classified according to a number of characteristics:\n\n===Simple vs. rounded=== <!--[[Minuet form]] redirects directly here.-->\n[[File:Oh, Susannah rounded binary form.png|thumb|400px|\"[[Oh! Susanna|Oh, Susannah]]\": rounded binary form.<ref>Kostka, Stefan and Payne, Dorothy (1995). ''Tonal Harmony'', p.343. 3rd edition, McGraw-Hill. {{ISBN|0-07-035874-5}}.</ref> {{audio|Oh, Susannah rounded binary form.mid|Play}}]]\n\nOccasionally, the ''B'' section will end with a \"return\" of the opening material from the ''A'' section.  This is referred to as '''rounded binary''', and is labeled as ''ABA''<nowiki>\u2032</nowiki>.  In rounded binary, the beginning of the ''B'' section is sometimes referred to as the \"bridge\", and will usually conclude with a [[cadence (music)|half cadence]] in the original key. Rounded binary is not to be confused with [[ternary form]], also labeled ''ABA''\u2014the difference being that, in ternary form, the ''B'' section contrasts completely with the ''A'' material as in, for example, a [[Minuet|minuet and trio]]. Another important difference between the rounded and ternary form is that in rounded binary, when the \"A\" section returns, it will typically contain only half of the full \"A\" section, whereas ternary form will end with the full \"A\" section.\n\nSometimes, as in the keyboard sonatas of [[Domenico Scarlatti]], the return of the ''A'' theme may include much of the original ''A'' section in the tonic key, so much so that some of his sonatas can be regarded as precursors of sonata form. \n\nRounded binary form is sometimes referred to as small ternary form.<ref name=\"Schoenberg\">Schoenberg, Arnold (1967). ''Fundamentals of Musical Composition'', p.119. {{ISBN|0-571-09276-4}}.</ref>\n\nRounded binary or '''minuet form''':<ref name=\"Rosen\">Rosen, Charles (1988). ''Sonata Forms'', p.29. {{ISBN|0-393-30219-9}}.</ref>\n A      :||: B                           A or A'\n I(->V) :||: V(or other [[closely related key|closely related]]) I\n\nIf the ''B'' section lacks such a return of the opening ''A'' material, the piece is said to be in '''simple binary'''.\n\nSimple:<ref name=\"Rosen\"/>\n A->B :||: A->B\n I->V :||: V->I\n\nSlow-movement form:<ref name=\"Rosen\"/>\n A'        A\"\n I->V      I->I\n\nMany examples of rounded binary are found among the church sonatas of Vivaldi including his Sonata No. 1 for Cello and Continuo, First Movement, while certain Baroque composers such as Bach and Handel used the form rarely.<ref>White, John D. (1976). ''The Analysis of Music'', p.51-52. {{ISBN|0-13-033233-X}}.</ref>\n\n===Sectional vs. continuous===\n[[File:Greensleeves sectional binary form.png|thumb|400px|\"Greensleeves\": sectional binary form (first phrase ends with the tonic).<ref>Kostka and Payne (1995), p.336.<!--ibid.--></ref> {{audio|Greensleeves sectional binary form.mid|Play}}]]. Note:  the example here is in minor mode rather than the more historically accurate Dorian mode.\n\nIf the ''A'' section ends with an Authentic (or Perfect) [[cadence (music)|cadence]] in the original [[tonic (music)|tonic]] key of the piece, the design is referred to as a '''sectional binary'''.  This refers to the fact that the piece is in different tonal sections, each beginning in their own respective keys.\n\nIf the ''A'' section ends with any other kind of cadence, the design is referred to as a '''continuous binary'''.  This refers to the fact that the ''B'' section will \"continue on\" with the new key established by the cadence at the end of ''A''.\n\n===Symmetrical vs. asymmetrical===\nIf the ''A'' and ''B'' sections are roughly equal in length, the design is referred to as '''symmetrical'''.\n\nIf the ''A'' and ''B'' sections are of unequal length, the design is referred to as '''asymmetrical'''.  In such cases, the ''B'' section is usually substantially longer than the ''A'' section.\n\nThe asymmetrical binary form begins to be more common than the symmetrical type from about the time of Beethoven onwards, and is almost routine in the main sections of Minuet and Trio or Scherzo and Trio movements in the works of many composers from Beethoven onwards.  In such cases, occasionally only the first section of the binary structure is marked to be repeated.\n\nAlthough most of [[Chopin nocturnes|Chopin's nocturne]]s are in an overall [[ternary form]], quite often the individual sections (either the A, the B, or both) are in binary form, most often of the asymmetrical variety.  If a section of this binary structure is repeated, in this case it is written out again in full, usually considerably varied, rather than enclosed between repeat signs.\n\n===Balanced binary===\nBalanced binary is when the end of the first section and the end of the second section have analogous material and are\norganized in a parallel way.\n\n==Sources==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{musical form}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Binary Form}}\n[[Category:Musical form]]\n[[Category:2 (number)]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the musical form}}\n[[Image:Binary form.png|thumb|400px|Binary form in major and minor keys. Each section must be at least three phrases long.<ref>White, John D. (1976). ''The Analysis of Music'', p.50. {{ISBN|0-13-033233-X}}.</ref>]]\n\n'''Binary form''' is a [[musical form]] in 2 related sections, both of which are usually repeated. Binary is also a structure used to choreograph [[dance]]. In music this is usually performed as A-A-B-B.\n\nBinary form was popular during the [[Baroque music|Baroque period]], often used to structure movements of [[keyboard instrument|keyboard]] [[sonata (music)|sonatas]]. It was also used for short, one-movement works.  Around the middle of the 18th century, the form largely fell from use as the principal design of entire movements as [[sonata form]] and organic [[musical development|development]] gained prominence. When it is found in later works, it usually takes the form of the theme in a set of [[variation form|variation]]s, or the [[Minuet]], [[Scherzo]], or Trio sections of a \"minuet and trio\" or \"scherzo and trio\" movement in a [[sonata]], [[symphony]], etc. Many larger forms incorporate binary structures, and many more complicated forms (such as the 18th-century [[sonata form]]) share certain characteristics with binary form.\n\n==Structure==\nMost strictly, a piece in binary form is characterized by two complementary, related sections of roughly equal duration, which come up frequently. The first section will start in a certain [[key (music)|key]], and will usually [[Modulation (music)|modulate]] to a [[closely related key|related key]]:\n*compositions in major keys will typically modulate to the [[dominant (music)|dominant]], the fifth scale degree above the [[tonic (music)|tonic]]\n*compositions in minor keys will typically modulate to the [[relative key|relative major]], the major key centered on the third scale degree above the tonic; alternatively the first section could close in the dominant minor, or with an imperfect [[cadence (music)|cadence]] in the original key.\n\nThe second section of the piece begins in the newly established key, where it remains for an indefinite period of time. After some  harmonic activity, the piece will eventually modulate back to its original key before ending. More often than not, especially in 18th-century compositions, the A and B sections are separated by [[bar (music)|double bars]] with repeat signs, meaning both sections were to be repeated.<ref>Bartlette, Christopher, and Steven G. Laitz (2010).  Graduate Review of Tonal Theory.  New York: Oxford University Press, pg 156.  {{ISBN|978-0-19-537698-2}}</ref>\n\nBinary form is usually characterised as having the form ''AB'', though since both sections repeat, a more accurate description would be ''AABB''.  Others, however, prefer to use the label ''AA\u2032''.  This second designation points to the fact that there is no great change in character between the two sections. The [[rhythm]]s and [[melody|melodic]] material used will generally be closely related in each section, and if the piece is written for a [[musical ensemble]], the [[Instrumentation (music)|instrumentation]] will generally be the same. This is in contrast to the use of [[verse-chorus form]] in [[popular music]]\u2014the contrast between the two sections is primarily one of the keys used.\n\n==Further distinctions==\nA piece in binary form can be further classified according to a number of characteristics:\n\n===Simple vs. rounded=== <!--[[Minuet form]] redirects directly here.-->\n[[File:Oh, Susannah rounded binary form.png|thumb|400px|\"[[Oh! Susanna|Oh, Susannah]]\": rounded binary form.<ref>Kostka, Stefan and Payne, Dorothy (1995). ''Tonal Harmony'', p.343. 3rd edition, McGraw-Hill. {{ISBN|0-07-035874-5}}.</ref> {{audio|Oh, Susannah rounded binary form.mid|Play}}]]\n\nOccasionally, the ''B'' section will end with a \"return\" of the opening material from the ''A'' section.  This is referred to as '''rounded binary''', and is labeled as ''ABA''<nowiki>\u2032</nowiki>.  In rounded binary, the beginning of the ''B'' section is sometimes referred to as the \"bridge\", and will usually conclude with a [[cadence (music)|half cadence]] in the original key. Rounded binary is not to be confused with [[ternary form]], also labeled ''ABA''\u2014the difference being that, in ternary form, the ''B'' section contrasts completely with the ''A'' material as in, for example, a [[Minuet|minuet and trio]]. Another important difference between the rounded and ternary form is that in rounded binary, when the \"A\" section returns, it will typically contain only half of the full \"A\" period, whereas ternary form will end with the full \"A\" section.\n\nSometimes, as in the keyboard sonatas of [[Domenico Scarlatti]], the return of the ''A'' theme may include much of the original ''A'' section in the tonic key, so much so that some of his sonatas can be regarded as precursors of sonata form. \n\nRounded binary form is sometimes referred to as small ternary form.<ref name=\"Schoenberg\">Schoenberg, Arnold (1967). ''Fundamentals of Musical Composition'', p.119. {{ISBN|0-571-09276-4}}.</ref>\n\nRounded binary or '''minuet form''':<ref name=\"Rosen\">Rosen, Charles (1988). ''Sonata Forms'', p.29. {{ISBN|0-393-30219-9}}.</ref>\n A      :||: B                           A or A'\n I(->V) :||: V(or other [[closely related key|closely related]]) I\n\nIf the ''B'' section lacks such a return of the opening ''A'' material, the piece is said to be in '''simple binary'''.\n\nSimple:<ref name=\"Rosen\"/>\n A->B :||: A->B\n I->V :||: V->I\n\nSlow-movement form:<ref name=\"Rosen\"/>\n A'        A\"\n I->V      I->I\n\nMany examples of rounded binary are found among the church sonatas of Vivaldi including his Sonata No. 1 for Cello and Continuo, First Movement, while certain Baroque composers such as Bach and Handel used the form rarely.<ref>White, John D. (1976). ''The Analysis of Music'', p.51-52. {{ISBN|0-13-033233-X}}.</ref>\n\n===Sectional vs. continuous===\n[[File:Greensleeves sectional binary form.png|thumb|400px|\"Greensleeves\": sectional binary form (first phrase ends with the tonic).<ref>Kostka and Payne (1995), p.336.<!--ibid.--></ref> {{audio|Greensleeves sectional binary form.mid|Play}}]]. Note:  the example here is in minor mode rather than the more historically accurate Dorian mode.\n\nIf the ''A'' section ends with an Authentic (or Perfect) [[cadence (music)|cadence]] in the original [[tonic (music)|tonic]] key of the piece, the design is referred to as a '''sectional binary'''.  This refers to the fact that the piece is in different tonal sections, each beginning in their own respective keys.\n\nIf the ''A'' section ends with any other kind of cadence, the design is referred to as a '''continuous binary'''.  This refers to the fact that the ''B'' section will \"continue on\" with the new key established by the cadence at the end of ''A''.\n\n===Symmetrical vs. asymmetrical===\nIf the ''A'' and ''B'' sections are roughly equal in length, the design is referred to as '''symmetrical'''.\n\nIf the ''A'' and ''B'' sections are of unequal length, the design is referred to as '''asymmetrical'''.  In such cases, the ''B'' section is usually substantially longer than the ''A'' section.\n\nThe asymmetrical binary form begins to be more common than the symmetrical type from about the time of Beethoven onwards, and is almost routine in the main sections of Minuet and Trio or Scherzo and Trio movements in the works of many composers from Beethoven onwards.  In such cases, occasionally only the first section of the binary structure is marked to be repeated.\n\nAlthough most of [[Chopin nocturnes|Chopin's nocturne]]s are in an overall [[ternary form]], quite often the individual sections (either the A, the B, or both) are in binary form, most often of the asymmetrical variety.  If a section of this binary structure is repeated, in this case it is written out again in full, usually considerably varied, rather than enclosed between repeat signs.\n\n===Balanced binary===\nBalanced binary is when the end of the first section and the end of the second section have analogous material and are\norganized in a parallel way.\n\n==Sources==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{musical form}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Binary Form}}\n[[Category:Musical form]]\n[[Category:2 (number)]]\n", "name_user": "88lives", "label": "safe", "comment": "The word \"period\" should be \"section\" instead. A \"section\" contains two \"periods\", which makes half of A equal to one full period.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binary_form"}
{"title_page": "Anna-Lena Forster", "text_new": "{{short description|German para-alpine skier}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name             = Anna-Lena Forster\n| image            = Women's sitting superg skier number 25.JPG\n| image_size       = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = Forster at the 2013 IPC World Championships\n<!-- Personal information -->\n| nickname         = \"Leni\", \"Lenchen\"\n| nationality      = German\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1995|06|15|df=yes}}\n| birth_place      = [[Radolfzell]], Germany\n| death_date       = \n| death_place      = \n| residence        = \n| alma_mater       = \n| occupation       = \n| years_active     = 2012\u2013\n| height           = \n| weight           = \n<!-- Sport -->\n| country          = Germany\n| sport            = [[Para-alpine skiing]]\n| disability       = \n| disability_class = [[LW12|LW12-1]]\n| event            = [[Downhill (ski competition)|Downhill]]<br/>[[Giant slalom]]<br/>[[Slalom skiing|Slalom]]<br/>[[Super-G]]<br/>[[Alpine skiing combined|Super combined]]\n| turnedpro        = \n| partner          = \n| former_partner   = \n| coach            = Justus Wolf\n| retired          = \n<!-- Achievements and titles -->\n| worlds           = \n| paralympics      = \n| highestranking   = \n<!-- Medal record -->\n| show-medals      = \n| medaltemplates   = \n{{MedalSport|Women's [[Alpine skiing]]}}\n{{MedalCountry|{{DEU}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Winter Paralympic Games]]}} \n{{MedalGold|[[2018 Winter Paralympics|2018 Pyeongchang]]|[[Alpine skiing at the 2018 Winter Paralympics \u2013 Women's slalom|Slalom sitting]]}}\n{{MedalGold|2018 Pyeongchang|[[Alpine skiing at the 2018 Winter Paralympics \u2013 Women's super combined|Super combined sitting]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[2014 Winter Paralympics|2014 Sochi]]|[[Alpine skiing at the 2014 Winter Paralympics \u2013 Women's combined|Super-combined sitting]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|2014 Sochi|[[Alpine skiing at the 2014 Winter Paralympics \u2013 Women's slalom|Slalom sitting]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|2014 Sochi|[[Alpine skiing at the 2014 Winter Paralympics \u2013 Women's giant slalom|Giant slalom sitting]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[IPC Alpine Skiing World Championships]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[2013 IPC Alpine Skiing World Championships|2013 La Molina]]|Slalom sitting}}\n{{MedalSilver|2017 Tarvisio|Slalom sitting}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[2015 IPC Alpine Skiing World Championships|2015 Panorama]]|Slalom sitting}}\n{{MedalBronze|2017 Tarvisio|Super combined sitting}}\n}}\n\n'''Anna-Lena Forster''' (born 15 June 1995) is a German [[para-alpine skiing|para-alpine skier]] who competed at the [[2014 Winter Paralympics|2014]] and [[2018 Winter Paralympics]], winning five medals.\n\n==Early life==\nForster was born in [[Radolfzell]], [[Konstanz (district)|Konstanz]] Germany. She was born without a right leg and with bones missing in her left leg.<ref name=ipc>{{cite web|title=Forster Anna-Lena|url=http://ipc.infostradasports.com/asp/lib/TheASP.asp?pageid=8937&sportid=564&personid=1103461|publisher=International Paralympic Committee|accessdate=12 August 2014}}</ref> She started skiing at the age of six at the VDK Munchen ski club.<ref name=ipc/>\n\n==Career==\nForster competes in the [[LW12]] [[para-alpine skiing classification]] using a [[mono-ski]] and [[Outrigger ski|outriggers]].<ref name=ipc/>\n\nAt the 2013 [[IPC Alpine Skiing World Championships]] held in [[La Molina (ski resort)|La Molina]], Spain, she won a silver medal in the women's [[Slalom skiing|slalom]] in a time of 2 minutes 31.31 seconds. She was also placed fourth in the super-combined and fifth in the [[super-G]] but she failed to finish the giant slalom.<ref name=ipc/>\n\nForster was selected as part of the [[Germany at the 2014 Winter Paralympics|German team]] for the [[2014 Winter Paralympics]] in [[Sochi]], Russia. Competing in the [[Alpine skiing at the 2014 Winter Paralympics \u2013 Women's slalom|slalom]] she finished in a time of 2 minutes 14.35 seconds and was identified as the gold medal winner and press releases announcing her victory were posted.<ref>{{cite news|title=Germany\u2019s Forster Skis to Paralympic Slalom Gold|url=http://en.ria.ru/sochi2014/20140312/188352849/Germanys-Forster-Skis-to-Paralympic-Slalom-Gold.html|accessdate=12 August 2014|agency=Ria Novosti|date=12 March 2014}}</ref> She was given gold because her compatriot [[Anna Schaffelhuber]], who finished in a faster time, was disqualified for not having her outriggers in a stationary position at the start of her first run.<ref name=ipc/><ref>{{cite news|title=Kimberly Joines to take bronze in slalom, not silver|url=http://www.cbc.ca/m/touch/sports/sports-paralympics/story/1.2570825|accessdate=12 August 2014|work=CBC Sports|date=13 March 2013}}</ref> Following an appeal Schaffelhuber was reinstated and Forster was awarded the silver medal.<ref>{{cite web|title=Schaffelhuber awarded gold after successful slalom appeal|url=http://www.paralympic.org/news/schaffelhuber-awarded-gold-after-successful-slalom-appeal|publisher=International Paralympic Committee|accessdate=12 August 2014|date=13 March 2014}}</ref> Forster won her second silver medal of the Games, again finishing behind Schaffelhuber, in the [[Alpine skiing at the 2014 Winter Paralympics \u2013 Women's combined|combined]]. The two German skiers were the only athletes to complete the race.<ref>{{cite web|title=Etherington wins historic silver |url=http://paralympics.channel4.com/competitions/sochi-2014-winter-paralympics/news/newsid=1239669/index.html |publisher=Channel4 |accessdate=12 August 2014 |date=14 March 2014 |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140812203158/http://paralympics.channel4.com/competitions/sochi-2014-winter-paralympics/news/newsid%3D1239669/index.html |archivedate=12 August 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Sochi 2014 Paralympic Winter Games Alpine Skiing Women's Super Combined sitting|url=http://www.paralympic.org/ipc_results/results2pdf.php?sport=alpine&competition=2014PWG&gender=f&discipline=&event=Super+Combined&eclass=sitting|publisher=International Paralympic Committee|accessdate=12 August 2014}}</ref> Her third Paralympic medal, a bronze, came in the [[Alpine skiing at the 2014 Winter Paralympics \u2013 Women's giant slalom|giant slalom]] where she finished behind Schaffelhuber and Austrian skier [[Claudia L\u00f6sch]] in a time of 2 minutes 59.33 seconds.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sochi 2014 Paralympic Winter Games Alpine Skiing Women's Giant Slalom sitting|url=http://www.paralympic.org/ipc_results/results2pdf.php?sport=alpine&competition=2014PWG&gender=f&discipline=&event=Giant+Slalom&eclass=sitting|publisher=International Paralympic Committee|accessdate=12 August 2014}}</ref> In the downhill Forster came fourth and therefore missed out on a medal. She failed to finish the super-G event.<ref name=ipc/>\n\nForster was nominated for the [[Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg|Baden]] Sports Personality of the Year award in 2012 and in 2013 she was awarded a gold medal by her home town of [[Radolfzell]] to mark her achievements.<ref name=ipc/>\n\n==References==\n{{Commons category|Anna-Lena Forster}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IPC athlete|id=anna-lena-forster|old_id=1103461}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Forster, Anna-Lena}}\n[[Category:1995 births]]\n[[Category:Alpine skiers at the 2014 Winter Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Alpine skiers at the 2018 Winter Paralympics]]\n[[Category:German female alpine skiers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2014 Winter Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2018 Winter Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Paralympic alpine skiers of Germany]]\n[[Category:Paralympic bronze medalists for Germany]]\n[[Category:Paralympic gold medalists for Germany]]\n[[Category:Paralympic silver medalists for Germany]]\n[[Category:People from Radolfzell]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|German para-alpine skier}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name             = Anna-Lena Forster\n| image            = Women's sitting superg skier number 25.JPG\n| image_size       = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = Forster at the 2013 IPC World Championships\n<!-- Personal information -->\n| nickname         = \"Leni\", \"Lenchen\"\n| nationality      = German\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1995|06|15|df=yes}}\n| birth_place      = [[Radolfzell]], Germany\n| death_date       = \n| death_place      = \n| residence        = \n| alma_mater       = \n| occupation       = \n| years_active     = 2012\u2013\n| height           = \n| weight           = \n<!-- Sport -->\n| country          = Germany\n| sport            = [[Para-alpine skiing]]\n| disability       = \n| disability_class = [[LW12|LW12-1]]\n| event            = [[Downhill (ski competition)|Downhill]]<br/>[[Giant slalom]]<br/>[[Slalom skiing|Slalom]]<br/>[[Super-G]]<br/>[[Alpine skiing combined|Super combined]]\n| turnedpro        = \n| partner          = \n| former_partner   = \n| coach            = Justus Wolf\n| retired          = \n<!-- Achievements and titles -->\n| worlds           = \n| paralympics      = \n| highestranking   = \n<!-- Medal record -->\n| show-medals      = \n| medaltemplates   = \n{{MedalSport|Women's [[Alpine skiing]]}}\n{{MedalCountry|{{DEU}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Winter Paralympic Games]]}} \n{{MedalGold|[[2018 Winter Paralympics|2018 Pyeongchang]]|[[Alpine skiing at the 2018 Winter Paralympics \u2013 Women's slalom|Slalom sitting]]}}\n{{MedalGold|2018 Pyeongchang|[[Alpine skiing at the 2018 Winter Paralympics \u2013 Women's super combined|Super combined sitting]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[2014 Winter Paralympics|2014 Sochi]]|[[Alpine skiing at the 2014 Winter Paralympics \u2013 Women's combined|Super-combined sitting]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|2014 Sochi|[[Alpine skiing at the 2014 Winter Paralympics \u2013 Women's slalom|Slalom sitting]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|2014 Sochi|[[Alpine skiing at the 2014 Winter Paralympics \u2013 Women's giant slalom|Giant slalom sitting]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[IPC Alpine Skiing World Championships]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[2013 IPC Alpine Skiing World Championships|2013 La Molina]]|Slalom sitting}}\n{{MedalSilver|2017 Tarvisio|Slalom sitting}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[2015 IPC Alpine Skiing World Championships|2015 Panorama]]|Slalom sitting}}\n{{MedalBronze|2017 Tarvisio|Super combined sitting}}\n}}\n\n'''Anna-Lena Forster''' (born 15 June 1995) is a German [[para-alpine skiing|para-alpine skier]] who competed at the [[2014 Winter Paralympics|2014]] and [[2018 Winter Paralympics]], winning five medals.\n\n==Early life==\nForster was born in [[Radolfzell]], [[Konstanz (district)|Konstanz]] Germany. She was born without a right leg and with bones missing in her left leg.<ref name=ipc>{{cite web|title=Forster Anna-Lena|url=http://ipc.infostradasports.com/asp/lib/TheASP.asp?pageid=8937&sportid=564&personid=1103461|publisher=International Paralympic Committee|accessdate=12 August 2014}}</ref> She started skiing at the age of six at the VDK Munchen ski club.<ref name=ipc/>\n\n==Career==\nForster competes in the [[LW12]] [[para-alpine skiing classification]] using a [[mono-ski]] and [[Outrigger ski|outriggers]].<ref name=ipc/>\n\nAt the 2013 [[IPC Alpine Skiing World Championships]] held in [[La Molina (ski resort)|La Molina]], Spain, she won a silver medal in the women's [[Slalom skiing|slalom]] in a time of 2 minutes 31.31 seconds. She was also placed fourth in the super-combined and fifth in the [[super-G]] but she failed to finish the giant slalom.<ref name=ipc/>\n\nForster was selected as part of the [[Germany at the 2014 Winter Paralympics|German team]] for the [[2014 Winter Paralympics]] in [[Sochi]], Russia. Competing in the [[Alpine skiing at the 2014 Winter Paralympics \u2013 Women's slalom|slalom]] she finished in a time of 2 minutes 14.35 seconds and was identified as the gold medal winner and press releases announcing her victory were posted.<ref>{{cite news|title=Germany\u2019s Forster Skis to Paralympic Slalom Gold|url=http://en.ria.ru/sochi2014/20140312/188352849/Germanys-Forster-Skis-to-Paralympic-Slalom-Gold.html|accessdate=12 August 2014|agency=Ria Novosti|date=12 March 2014}}</ref> She was given gold because her compatriot [[Anna Schaffelhuber]], who finished in a faster time, was disqualified for not having her outriggers in a stationary position at the start of her first run.<ref name=ipc/><ref>{{cite news|title=Kimberly Joines to take bronze in slalom, not silver|url=http://www.cbc.ca/m/touch/sports/sports-paralympics/story/1.2570825|accessdate=12 August 2014|work=CBC Sports|date=13 March 2013}}</ref> Following an appeal Schaffelhuber was reinstated and Forster was awarded the silver medal.<ref>{{cite web|title=Schaffelhuber awarded gold after successful slalom appeal|url=http://www.paralympic.org/news/schaffelhuber-awarded-gold-after-successful-slalom-appeal|publisher=International Paralympic Committee|accessdate=12 August 2014|date=13 March 2014}}</ref> Forster won her second silver medal of the Games, again finishing behind Schaffelhuber, in the [[Alpine skiing at the 2014 Winter Paralympics \u2013 Women's combined|combined]]. The two German skiers were the only athletes to complete the race.<ref>{{cite web|title=Etherington wins historic silver |url=http://paralympics.channel4.com/competitions/sochi-2014-winter-paralympics/news/newsid=1239669/index.html |publisher=Channel4 |accessdate=12 August 2014 |date=14 March 2014 |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140812203158/http://paralympics.channel4.com/competitions/sochi-2014-winter-paralympics/news/newsid%3D1239669/index.html |archivedate=12 August 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Sochi 2014 Paralympic Winter Games Alpine Skiing Women's Super Combined sitting|url=http://www.paralympic.org/ipc_results/results2pdf.php?sport=alpine&competition=2014PWG&gender=f&discipline=&event=Super+Combined&eclass=sitting|publisher=International Paralympic Committee|accessdate=12 August 2014}}</ref> Her third Paralympic medal, a bronze, came in the [[Alpine skiing at the 2014 Winter Paralympics \u2013 Women's giant slalom|giant slalom]] where she finished behind Schaffelhuber and Austrian skier [[Claudia L\u00f6sch]] in a time of 2 minutes 59.33 seconds.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sochi 2014 Paralympic Winter Games Alpine Skiing Women's Giant Slalom sitting|url=http://www.paralympic.org/ipc_results/results2pdf.php?sport=alpine&competition=2014PWG&gender=f&discipline=&event=Giant+Slalom&eclass=sitting|publisher=International Paralympic Committee|accessdate=12 August 2014}}</ref> In the downhill Forster came fourth and therefore missed out on a medal. She failed to finish the super-G event.<ref name=ipc/>\n\nForster was nominated for the [[Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg|Baden]] Sports Personality of the Year award in 2012 and in 2013 she was awarded a gold medal by her home town of [[Radolfzell]] to mark her achievements.<ref name=ipc/>\n\n==References==\n{{Commons category|Anna-Lena Forster}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IPC athlete|1103461}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Forster, Anna-Lena}}\n[[Category:1995 births]]\n[[Category:Alpine skiers at the 2014 Winter Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Alpine skiers at the 2018 Winter Paralympics]]\n[[Category:German female alpine skiers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2014 Winter Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2018 Winter Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Paralympic alpine skiers of Germany]]\n[[Category:Paralympic bronze medalists for Germany]]\n[[Category:Paralympic gold medalists for Germany]]\n[[Category:Paralympic silver medalists for Germany]]\n[[Category:People from Radolfzell]]\n", "name_user": "Zyxw", "label": "safe", "comment": "update IPC external link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anna-Lena_Forster"}
{"title_page": "Monomoy Regional High School", "text_new": "{{More citations needed|date=November 2010}}\n{{Infobox school\n| name = Monomoy Regional High School\n| type = [[State school|Public]]<br>[[School choice|Open enrollment]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.doe.mass.edu/finance/schoolchoice/choice-status.pdf|title=Massachusetts Department of Elementary and Secondary Education - Error Page|website=www.doe.mass.edu|accessdate=Aug 2, 2019}}</ref>\n| established = 2014\n| principal = Mr. William Burkhead\n| superintendent = Mr. Scott Carpenter\n| campus = Suburban\n| grades = 8\u201312\n| enrollment = 620 (2017-18)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nces.ed.gov/ccd/schoolsearch/school_detail.asp?Search=1&DistrictID=2500544&ID=250054402836|title=Monomoy Regional High School|publisher=National Center for Education Statistics|accessdate=February 9, 2019}}</ref>\n| budget = $35,186,124 total<br>$16,135 per pupil<br>(2016)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://profiles.doe.mass.edu/statereport/ppx.aspx|title=Massachusetts Department Of Elementary And Secondary Education - Per Pupil Expenditures Statewide Report|website=profiles.doe.mass.edu|accessdate=Aug 2, 2019}}</ref>\n| SAT = 578 verbal<br />567 math<br />1145 total (2017-2018)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://profiles.doe.mass.edu/statereport/sat.aspx|title=Massachusetts Department Of Elementary And Secondary Education - 2017-18 SAT Performance Report - All Students Statewide Report|website=profiles.doe.mass.edu|accessdate=Aug 2, 2019}}</ref>\n| communities = [[Chatham, Massachusetts|Chatham]] & [[Harwich, Massachusetts|Harwich]]\n| mascot = Sharks\n| colors = Blue, Silver, White {{Color box|darkblue|border=darkgray}} {{Color box|silver|border=darkgray}} {{Color box|white|border=darkgray}}\n| rivals = [[Nauset Regional High School|Nauset]], [[Dennis-Yarmouth Regional High School|D-Y]], [[Cape Cod Regional Technical High School|Cape Tech]], [[Nantucket High School|Nantucket]]\n| conference = Cape & Islands League\n| location = 75 Oak St.<br />Harwich, Massachusetts 02645\n| coordinates = {{Coord|41|41|26.41|N|70|04|12.95|W|type:edu_region:US-MA|display=inline,title}}\n| website = [http://www.monomoy.edu Monomoy Regional School District]\n}}\n\n'''Monomoy Regional High School''' is a regional [[secondary school]] located in [[Harwich, Massachusetts|Harwich]], [[Massachusetts]], within [[Barnstable County, Massachusetts|Barnstable County]]. Monomoy Regional High School serves approximately 625 students in grades 8-12 from the towns of [[Chatham, Massachusetts|Chatham]] and [[Harwich, Massachusetts|Harwich]].\n\nConstruction of the high school was completed in early 2014 and officially opened in September 2014. The school's mascot is the Sharks and the [[school colors]] are Navy Blue & Silver.\n\n==Athletics==\n\nAll the athletic teams from [[Harwich High School]] and [[Chatham High School (Massachusetts)|Chatham High School]] began competing cooperatively as the Monomoy Sharks in Fall 2012 for all sports offered by both schools.\n\nMonomoy offers 20 interscholastic athletic teams along with multiple club and intramural teams. As of 2016, Monomoy is a member of the Cape & Islands League, which competes in the Division 4 level of athletic competition in Massachusetts, and is affiliated with the [[Massachusetts Interscholastic Athletic Association]].\n\nIn May 2015, Monomoy Regional High School gained approval from the South Shore League at the annual league meeting to leave the league and join the Cape & Islands League,<ref>{{cite news|author1=Dan Ventura|title=Monomoy slated to join the Cape & Islands League in September of 2016|url=http://www.bostonherald.com/sports/high_school/high_school_insider/2015/05/monomoy_slated_to_join_the_cape_islands_league_in|newspaper=[[Boston Herald]]|accessdate=26 November 2015|date=7 May 2015}}</ref> citing travel expenses and competition as the main factors regarding their departure. Monomoy was a member of the South Shore League since the mid-1990s. The change will take effect during the beginning of the 2016\u201317 academic year. The football team's league affiliation is in question due to the change, as the Cape & Islands League does not sponsor football. Ultimately, the Sharks will either continue to compete in the South Shore League as a football only member, or pursue an independent schedule with no league affiliation. With the departure of Monomoy, [[Mashpee High School|Mashpee]] is left as the South Shore League's lone representative from [[Cape Cod]].\n\nRecent Success in Sports: The Monomoy High School's Basketball team went from 1-19 in 2015-2016 while competing in the South Shore League to 15-6 after switching into the Cape and Islands League. The team went under a controversial time after the school's administration decided to fire beloved Coach and Harwich High School Alumni Adam Rose. Rose was then hired as a head coach at [[Cape Cod Academy|CCA]]. Monomoy then hired Coach Keith Arnold a former [[Dennis-Yarmouth Regional High School|DY]] and [[Nauset Regional High School|Nauset]] boys basketball coach to take over. The team won the Cape and Islands Large League Title and also made it to the Division 4 South Sectional Finals as the #9 seed after beating [[Sturgis Charter Public School|Sturgis East]], [[Southeastern Regional Vocational Technical High School|Southeastern]], and [[Old Colony Regional Vocational Technical High School|Old Colony]] in the MIAA tournament. Later on the team would lose to D4 powerhouse [[Cathedral High School (Boston)|Cathedral Catholic]]. It was an amazing cinderella run in the MIAA tournament for the Sharks.\n\n* Listed below are the sports offered at Monomoy Regional High School.\n\n'''FALL'''\n* Football\n* Field Hockey\n* Boys' Soccer\n* Girls' Soccer\n* Cheerleading\n* Cross Country\n* Boys' Golf\n\n'''WINTER'''\n* Boys' Basketball\n* Girls' Basketball\n* Ice Hockey (co-op with [[Mashpee High School|Mashpee]])\n* Cheerleading\n\n'''SPRING'''\n* Baseball\n* Softball\n* Boys' Tennis\n* Girls' Tennis\n* Boys' Lacrosse\n* Girls' Lacrosse\n* Track & Field\n* Sailing\n* Girls' Golf\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n* [http://www.wickedlocal.com/capecod/news/x1081598225/Monomoy-High-School-cost-estimated-at-65-4-million#axzz21Niks6p7 Monomoy High School cost estimated at $65.4 million]\n\n{{Massachusetts Public High Schools}}\n\n[[Category:Chatham, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Public high schools in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:High schools in Harwich, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:2014 establishments in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 2014]]\n", "text_old": "{{More citations needed|date=November 2010}}\n{{Infobox school\n| name = Monomoy Regional High School\n| type = [[State school|Public]]<br>[[School choice|Open enrollment]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.doe.mass.edu/finance/schoolchoice/choice-status.pdf|title=Massachusetts Department of Elementary and Secondary Education - Error Page|website=www.doe.mass.edu|accessdate=Aug 2, 2019}}</ref>\n| established = 2014\n| principal = Mr. William Burkhead\n| superintendent = Mr. Scott Carpenter\n| campus = Suburban\n| grades = 8\u201312\n| enrollment = 620 (2017-18)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nces.ed.gov/ccd/schoolsearch/school_detail.asp?Search=1&DistrictID=2500544&ID=250054402836|title=Monomoy Regional High School|publisher=National Center for Education Statistics|accessdate=February 9, 2019}}</ref>\n| budget = $35,186,124 total<br>$16,135 per pupil<br>(2016)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://profiles.doe.mass.edu/statereport/ppx.aspx|title=Massachusetts Department Of Elementary And Secondary Education - Per Pupil Expenditures Statewide Report|website=profiles.doe.mass.edu|accessdate=Aug 2, 2019}}</ref>\n| SAT = 578 verbal<br />567 math<br />1145 total (2017-2018)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://profiles.doe.mass.edu/statereport/sat.aspx|title=Massachusetts Department Of Elementary And Secondary Education - 2017-18 SAT Performance Report - All Students Statewide Report|website=profiles.doe.mass.edu|accessdate=Aug 2, 2019}}</ref>\n| communities = [[Chatham, Massachusetts|Chatham]] & [[Harwich, Massachusetts|Harwich]]\n| mascot = Sharks\n| colors = Blue, Silver, White {{Color box|darkblue|border=darkgray}} {{Color box|silver|border=darkgray}} {{Color box|white|border=darkgray}}\n| rivals = [[Nauset Regional High School|Nauset]], [[Dennis-Yarmouth Regional High School|D-Y]], [[Cape Cod Regional Technical High School|Cape Tech]], [[Nantucket High School|Nantucket]]\n| conference = Cape & Islands League\n| location = 75 Oak St.<br />Harwich, Massachusetts 02645\n| coordinates = {{Coord|41|41|26.41|N|70|04|12.95|W|type:edu_region:US-MA|display=inline,title}}\n| website = [http://www.monomoy.edu Monomoy Regional School District]\n}}\n\n'''Monomoy Regional High School''' is a regional [[secondary school]] located in [[Harwich, Massachusetts|Harwich]], [[Massachusetts]], within [[Barnstable County, Massachusetts|Barnstable County]]. Monomoy Regional High School serves approximately 625 students in grades 8-12 from the towns of [[Chatham, Massachusetts|Chatham]] and [[Harwich, Massachusetts|Harwich]].\n\nConstruction of the high school was completed in early 2014 and officially opened in September 2014. The school's mascot is the Sharks and the [[school colors]] are Navy Blue & Silver.\n\n==Athletics==\n\nAll the athletic teams from [[Harwich High School]] and [[Chatham High School (Massachusetts)|Chatham High School]] began competing cooperatively as the Monomoy Sharks in Fall 2012 for all sports offered by both schools.\n\nMonomoy offers 20 interscholastic athletic teams along with multiple club and intramural teams. As of 2016, Monomoy is a member of the Cape & Islands League, which competes in the Division 4 level of athletic competition in Massachusetts, and is affiliated with the [[Massachusetts Interscholastic Athletic Association]].\n\nIn May 2015, Monomoy Regional High School gained approval from the South Shore League at the annual league meeting to leave the league and join the Cape & Islands League,<ref>{{cite news|author1=Dan Ventura|title=Monomoy slated to join the Cape & Islands League in September of 2016|url=http://www.bostonherald.com/sports/high_school/high_school_insider/2015/05/monomoy_slated_to_join_the_cape_islands_league_in|newspaper=[[Boston Herald]]|accessdate=26 November 2015|date=7 May 2015}}</ref> citing travel expenses and competition as the main factors regarding their departure. Monomoy was a member of the South Shore League since the mid-1990s. The change will take effect during the beginning of the 2016\u201317 academic year. The football team's league affiliation is in question due to the change, as the Cape & Islands League does not sponsor football. Ultimately, the Sharks will either continue to compete in the South Shore League as a football only member, or pursue an independent schedule with no league affiliation. With the departure of Monomoy, [[Mashpee High School|Mashpee]] is left as the South Shore League's lone representative from [[Cape Cod]].\n\nRecent Success in Sports: The Monomoy High School's Basketball team went from 1-19 in 2015-2016 while competing in the South Shore League to 15-6 after switching into the Cape and Islands League. The team went under a controversial time after the school's administration decided to fire beloved Coach and Harwich High School Alumni Adam Rose. Rose was then hired as a head coach at [[Cape Cod Academy|CCA]]. Monomoy then hired Coach Keith Arnold a former [[Dennis-Yarmouth Regional High School|DY]] and [[Nauset Regional High School|Nauset]] boys basketball coach to take over. Part of the team's core of Junior-Meehan and Senior-Mazulis were [[Nauset Regional High School|Nauset]] Transfers who founded the foundation for Monomoy Basketball success. The team won the Cape and Islands Large League Title and also made it to the Division 4 South Sectional Finals as the #9 seed after beating [[Sturgis Charter Public School|Sturgis East]], [[Southeastern Regional Vocational Technical High School|Southeastern]], and [[Old Colony Regional Vocational Technical High School|Old Colony]] in the MIAA tournament. Later on the team would lose to D4 powerhouse [[Cathedral High School (Boston)|Cathedral Catholic]]. Players Nick Meehan, Chris Mazulis, Sam Reed and Eli Nickerson were vital to this team's cinderella run in the MIAA tournament.\n\n* Listed below are the sports offered at Monomoy Regional High School.\n\n'''FALL'''\n* Football\n* Field Hockey\n* Boys' Soccer\n* Girls' Soccer\n* Cheerleading\n* Cross Country\n* Boys' Golf\n\n'''WINTER'''\n* Boys' Basketball\n* Girls' Basketball\n* Ice Hockey (co-op with [[Mashpee High School|Mashpee]])\n* Cheerleading\n\n'''SPRING'''\n* Baseball\n* Softball\n* Boys' Tennis\n* Girls' Tennis\n* Boys' Lacrosse\n* Girls' Lacrosse\n* Track & Field\n* Sailing\n* Girls' Golf\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n* [http://www.wickedlocal.com/capecod/news/x1081598225/Monomoy-High-School-cost-estimated-at-65-4-million#axzz21Niks6p7 Monomoy High School cost estimated at $65.4 million]\n\n{{Massachusetts Public High Schools}}\n\n[[Category:Chatham, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Public high schools in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:High schools in Harwich, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:2014 establishments in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 2014]]\n", "name_user": "73.16.187.21", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eAthletics:Lmao ppl lying)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monomoy_Regional_High_School"}
{"title_page": "Nang Khin Zay Yar", "text_new": "{{Burmese name|Nang}}\n{{Infobox pageant titleholder\n| name=Nang Khin Zay Yar\n| native_name = {{my|\u1014\u1014\u103a\u1038\u1001\u1004\u103a\u1007\u1031\u101a\u103b\u102c}}\n| image= Nang Khin Zay Yar.jpg\n| caption = Nang Khin Zay Yar at Miss International 2012 in [[Okinawa]]\n| birth_place= [[Taunggyi|Taunggyi, Myanmar]]\n| birth_name= Nang Khin Zay Yar\n| birth_date= {{birth date and age|df=yes|1988|3|4}}\n| education = B.A Law (LL.B)\n| occupation = [[Tour guide]], [[Model (person)|Model]]\n| years_active= 2011 -\n| residence = [[Myanmar]]\n| height={{height|ft=5|in=6.5}}  \n| measurements = \n| eye_color= Black\n| hair_color= Dark\n| title= Miss Myanmar 2012<ref name=\"Miss Myanmar 2012\" /><br>Miss Yangon 2012\n| competitions=Miss Myanmar 2012 (Winner)<br>[[Miss International 2012]] (Miss Internet)<ref name=\"Participating in Miss International\" />\n| signature = Nang Khin Zay Yar Signature.gif\n}}\n\n'''Nang Khin Zay Yar''' ({{lang-my|\u1014\u1014\u103a\u1038\u1001\u1004\u103a\u1007\u1031\u101a\u103b\u102c}}; born in Taunggyi on March 4, 1988) is a Burmese model, actress and beauty pageant titleholder who won [[Miss Universe Myanmar]] title in 2012.<ref name=\"Miss Myanmar 2012\">[http://info.myanmarcelebrity.com/2012/03/video-miss-myanmar-2012-beauty-contest.html Video: Miss Myanmar 2012 Beauty Contest in Yangon ~ Myanmar Celebrity: All about Myanmar Celebrities<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> She is a [[Pa'O people|Shan- Pa'O]], which are ethnic minorities from Myanmar. She also won the Missosology's Miss International 2012 People's Choice Award, Pageantology.net Miss International 2012 People's Choice Award and Miss Internet Award in [[Miss International 2012]], [[Okinawa]].<ref name=\"Participating in Miss International\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20121006065655/http://missinternational-okinawa.com/pageants/ The Pagents{{sic|hide=y}} | Miss International 2012 in Okinawa<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n==Early life==\n\nNang Khin Zay Yar was born in [[Taunggyi]] on March 4, 1988 to her mother Nang Phyu Phyu Khine and her father Khun Aung Myat. Nang Khin Zay Yar went to Basic Education High School No. 4 Taunggyi. Nang Khin Zay Yar finished her education from [[Taunggyi University]], earning her degree as a [[Bachelor of Laws]]. After she finished her education, she opted to become a tour guide instead of a [[lawyer]], shortly afterwards moving into model industry.<ref name=\"Youtube Nang Khin Zay Yar\">[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PfUCohmNWVs Photo Making with Miss Myanmar 2012 - Nang Khin Zay Yar - YouTube<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> She can speak both [[English language|English]] and [[German language|German]].\n\n==Career==\n\nNang Khin Zay Yar became a model in 2011, taking photos for magazines, journals and model websites. In 2012, shortly after she won the title of Miss Myanmar 2012, she was offered to shoot for some advertisements. Currently she is appearing on many Burmese videos and movies as an actress. Although she does not have a clear intention to be a singer so soon, she is already singing both in local and foreign shows and concerts.<ref name=\"Youtube Nang Khin Zay Yar\"/>\n\n==Personal life==\n\nNang Khin Zay Yar is single. Her religion is [[Buddhism]]. She currently lives in [[Yangon, Myanmar]]. She is still working as a tour guide even though she's already a model.\n\n==Competitions==\n\n===Miss Myanmar 2012===\n\nNang Khin Zay Yar competed in Miss Myanmar 2012 which was held on March 25, 2012 at Myanmar Convention Center (MCC), [[Yangon]]. The competition was organized by the Myanmar Tourism Services (MTS) Co., under the supervision of Myanmar Travel Board (MTB) in order to promote tourism industry in the country and enhance the interest of citizens in the tourism sector. Nann Khin Zayar won Miss Yangon title, Miss Myanmar 2012 title and she was assigned as a tourism Ambassador of Myanmar.\n\n===Miss International 2012===\n\nNang Khin Zay Yar participated in [[Miss International 2012]] which is in [[Okinawa]].<ref name=\"Participating in Miss International\" /> This is the first time [[Myanmar]] competed in an international beauty pageant since 1962. The Final was on October 21, 2012.<ref name=\"Myanmar Opens Up\">[http://missosology.org/missinternational/featured/item/1393-myanmar-opens-up Myanmar opens up]</ref> Nang Khin Zay Yar already won Pageantology.net Miss International 2012 People's Choice Award, Missosology's Miss International 2012 People's Choice Award on the night of October 20, 2012.<ref name=\"Myanmar won People's choice Award\">[http://missosology.org/missinternational/news/item/1508-myanmar-wins-missosologys-peoples-choice-award Myanmar's Nang Khin Zay Yar won, Missosology Miss International 2012 People's Choice Award]</ref> She won the Miss Internet Award in the competition.<ref name=\"Miss Myanmar won Miss Inernet\">[http://missinternational-okinawa.com/final/ Myanmar won Miss Internet]</ref>\n\n==References==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.facebook.com/pages/Nang-Khin-Zay-Yar/460414564009143?ref=ts&fref=ts Nang Khin Zay Yar] on [[Facebook]]\n*{{Twitter}}\n*[http://nangkhinzayyar.tumblr.com/ Nang Khin Zar Yar] on [[Tumblr]]\n{{Miss International 2012 delegates}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nang Khin Zay Yar}}\n[[Category:1988 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Burmese beauty pageant winners]]\n[[Category:Burmese female models]]\n[[Category:People from Shan State]]\n[[Category:Burmese people of Shan descent]]\n[[Category:People from Taunggyi]]\n[[Category:Burmese Buddhists]]\n[[Category:Miss International 2012 delegates]]\n", "text_old": "{{Burmese name|Nang}}\n{{Infobox pageant titleholder\n| name=Nang Khin Zay Yar\n| native_name = {{my|\u1014\u1014\u103a\u1038\u1001\u1004\u103a\u1007\u1031\u101a\u103b\u102c}}\n| image= Nang Khin Zay Yar.jpg\n| caption = Nang Khin Zay Yar at Miss International 2012 in [[Okinawa]]\n| birth_place= [[Taunggyi|Taunggyi, Myanmar]]\n| birth_name= Nang Khin Zay Yar\n| birth_date= {{birth date and age|df=yes|1988|3|4}}\n| education = B.A Law (LL.B)\n| occupation = [[Tour guide]], [[Model (person)|Model]]\n| years_active= 2011 -\n| residence = [[Myanmar]]\n| height={{height|ft=5|in=6.5}}  \n| measurements = \n| eye_color= Black\n| hair_color= Dark\n| title= Miss Myanmar 2012<ref name=\"Miss Myanmar 2012\" /><br>Miss Yangon 2012\n| competitions=Miss Myanmar 2012 (Winner)<br>[[Miss International 2012]] (Miss Internet)<ref name=\"Participating in Miss International\" />\n| signature = Nang Khin Zay Yar Signature.gif\n}}\n\n'''Nang Khin Zay Yar''' ({{lang-my|\u1014\u1014\u103a\u1038\u1001\u1004\u103a\u1007\u1031\u101a\u103b\u102c}}; born in Taunggyi on March 4, 1988) is a Burmese model, actress and beauty pageant titleholder who won [[Miss Universe Myanmar]] title in 2012.<ref name=\"Miss Myanmar 2012\">[http://info.myanmarcelebrity.com/2012/03/video-miss-myanmar-2012-beauty-contest.html Video: Miss Myanmar 2012 Beauty Contest in Yangon ~ Myanmar Celebrity: All about Myanmar Celebrities<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> She is a [[Pa'O people|Shan- Pa'O]], which are ethnic minorities from Myanmar. She also won the Missosology's Miss International 2012 People's Choice Award, Pageantology.net Miss International 2012 People's Choice Award and Miss Internet Award in [[Miss International 2012]], [[Okinawa]].<ref name=\"Participating in Miss International\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20121006065655/http://missinternational-okinawa.com/pageants/ The Pagents | Miss International 2012 in Okinawa<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n==Early life==\n\nNang Khin Zay Yar was born in [[Taunggyi]] on March 4, 1988 to her mother Nang Phyu Phyu Khine and her father Khun Aung Myat. Nang Khin Zay Yar went to Basic Education High School No. 4 Taunggyi. Nang Khin Zay Yar finished her education from [[Taunggyi University]], earning her degree as a [[Bachelor of Laws]]. After she finished her education, she opted to become a tour guide instead of a [[lawyer]], shortly afterwards moving into model industry.<ref name=\"Youtube Nang Khin Zay Yar\">[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PfUCohmNWVs Photo Making with Miss Myanmar 2012 - Nang Khin Zay Yar - YouTube<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> She can speak both [[English language|English]] and [[German language|German]].\n\n==Career==\n\nNang Khin Zay Yar became a model in 2011, taking photos for magazines, journals and model websites. In 2012, shortly after she won the title of Miss Myanmar 2012, she was offered to shoot for some advertisements. Currently she is appearing on many Burmese videos and movies as an actress. Although she does not have a clear intention to be a singer so soon, she is already singing both in local and foreign shows and concerts.<ref name=\"Youtube Nang Khin Zay Yar\"/>\n\n==Personal life==\n\nNang Khin Zay Yar is single. Her religion is [[Buddhism]]. She currently lives in [[Yangon, Myanmar]]. She is still working as a tour guide even though she's already a model.\n\n==Competitions==\n\n===Miss Myanmar 2012===\n\nNang Khin Zay Yar competed in Miss Myanmar 2012 which was held on March 25, 2012 at Myanmar Convention Center (MCC), [[Yangon]]. The competition was organized by the Myanmar Tourism Services (MTS) Co., under the supervision of Myanmar Travel Board (MTB) in order to promote tourism industry in the country and enhance the interest of citizens in the tourism sector. Nann Khin Zayar won Miss Yangon title, Miss Myanmar 2012 title and she was assigned as a tourism Ambassador of Myanmar.\n\n===Miss International 2012===\n\nNang Khin Zay Yar participated in [[Miss International 2012]] which is in [[Okinawa]].<ref name=\"Participating in Miss International\" /> This is the first time [[Myanmar]] competed in an international beauty pageant since 1962. The Final was on October 21, 2012.<ref name=\"Myanmar Opens Up\">[http://missosology.org/missinternational/featured/item/1393-myanmar-opens-up Myanmar opens up]</ref> Nang Khin Zay Yar already won Pageantology.net Miss International 2012 People's Choice Award, Missosology's Miss International 2012 People's Choice Award on the night of October 20, 2012.<ref name=\"Myanmar won People's choice Award\">[http://missosology.org/missinternational/news/item/1508-myanmar-wins-missosologys-peoples-choice-award Myanmar's Nang Khin Zay Yar won, Missosology Miss International 2012 People's Choice Award]</ref> She won the Miss Internet Award in the competition.<ref name=\"Miss Myanmar won Miss Inernet\">[http://missinternational-okinawa.com/final/ Myanmar won Miss Internet]</ref>\n\n==References==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.facebook.com/pages/Nang-Khin-Zay-Yar/460414564009143?ref=ts&fref=ts Nang Khin Zay Yar] on [[Facebook]]\n*{{Twitter}}\n*[http://nangkhinzayyar.tumblr.com/ Nang Khin Zar Yar] on [[Tumblr]]\n{{Miss International 2012 delegates}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nang Khin Zay Yar}}\n[[Category:1988 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Burmese beauty pageant winners]]\n[[Category:Burmese female models]]\n[[Category:People from Shan State]]\n[[Category:Burmese people of Shan descent]]\n[[Category:People from Taunggyi]]\n[[Category:Burmese Buddhists]]\n[[Category:Miss International 2012 delegates]]\n", "name_user": "Will Sandberg", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nang_Khin_Zay_Yar"}
